{"title_page": "Jay Ruderman", "text_new": "{{NPOV language|date=March 2020}}\n{{Peacock|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jay Ruderman\n| image              = Jay Ruderman April 2014.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Jay Ruderman (April 2014)\n| birth_name         = Jay Seth Ruderman\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1966|3|16}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Activist and philanthropist\n| children           = \n| parents            = Morton Edward Ruderman, Marcia Jortner Ruderman\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Shira Menashe Ruderman|2002}}\n}}\n'''Jay Seth Ruderman''' (born March 16, 1966) is an American activist and philanthropist. He is the president of the [[Ruderman Family Foundation]].\n \n==Early life and education==\nRuderman was born on March 16, 1966. He is the oldest of three siblings, the son of Marcia and Morton E. Ruderman.<ref>{{cite web | last=Negri | first=Gloria | title=Morton Ruderman, 75; devoted life to helping others | website=BostonGlobe.com | date=2011-10-31 | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/obituaries/2011/10/31/morton-ruderman-devoted-life-helping-others/rL8YpiDtdYBG1iWAWLgpwI/story.html | access-date=2018-02-22}}</ref> Ruderman attended public schools in [[Lynnfield, Massachusetts]], and received his undergraduate degree in 1988 from [[Brandeis University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandeis.edu/commencement/2018/honorees/ruderman-jay.html|title=Jay Ruderman \u201988 - Commencement - Brandeis University|author=|date=|website=www.brandeis.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> where he served as president of the student body in 1986\u201387. He earned his [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from [[Boston University School of Law]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/tag/class-of-1993/|title=Class of 1993 - School of Law|author=|date=|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> He began his career as Assistant District Attorney in Salem, MA and also worked as Deputy Director of AIPAC  before enlisting in the Israeli Defense Forces. He then went back to AIPAC as Leadership Director in Israel before taking his job at the Ruderman Family Foundation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncfp.org/people/jay-ruderman/|title=Jay Ruderman \u2013 NCFP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Commentary on popular culture==\nRuderman publicly criticized the movie ''[[Don't Worry, He Won't Get Far on Foot]]'' for casting [[Joaquin Phoenix]] in the role of a disabled man, instead of casting an actor with a disability.<ref>[https://www.indiewire.com/2018/01/joaquin-phoenix-casting-dont-worry-he-wont-get-far-on-foot-ruderman-disability-foundation-1201918359/ \"Joaquin Phoenix\u2019s \u2018Don\u2019t Worry, He Won\u2019t Get Far on Foot\u2019 Casting Slammed as Offensive by Ruderman Disability Foundation\"] ''IndieWire''. Retrieved 2018-03-22.</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Ruderman similarly condemned<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/alec-baldwin-criticized-for-portraying-blind-man-in-new-film-w491281|title=Alec Baldwin Criticized for Portraying Blind Man in Upcoming Film|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> the movie ''[[Blind (2016 film)|Blind]]'' starring [[Alec Baldwin]] and [[Demi Moore]] on grounds that Baldwin played a blind character. Ruderman's main claim is that the movie \"is just the latest example of treating disability as a costume.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/blind-alec-baldwin-controversy-1202488128/|title=Disability Organization Slams \u2018Blind\u2019 for Casting Alec Baldwin in Lead Role|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|date=July 6, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=July 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-july-disability-organization-condemns-1499273816-htmlstory.html|title=Today in Entertainment: Blue Ivy makes her rap debut on Jay-Z's new album; Angela Lansbury, Emily Watson to star in 'Little Women'|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> He likened the casting of able-bodied actors to portray characters with disabilities to blackface<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jul/06/how-alec-baldwin-casting-in-blind-is-part-of-a-catch-22-for-disabled-actors|title=How Alec Baldwin's casting in Blind is part of a catch-22 for disabled actors|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=2017-07-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and states that it's time for society to condemn the practice just like casting white actors to play black characters is no longer socially acceptable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/07/alec-baldwin-new-movie-blind-disability-rights-ableism-1201851800/|title=Alec Baldwin\u2019s New Movie \u2018Blind\u2019 Criticized By Disability Rights Group {{!}} IndieWire|last=Dry|first=Jude|website=www.indiewire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> The incident led to written exchanges between the movie's director, [[Michael Mailer]], and Ruderman, both published by the industry publication Deadline.com.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/blind-alec-baldwin-backlash-director-responds-michael-mailer-1202129011/|title=\u2018Blind\u2019 Director Addresses Backlash Over Casting Alec Baldwin And Not Disabled Actor In Lead Role|last=Mailer|first=Michael|date=2017-07-14|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-20|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/blind-movie-controversy-alec-baldwin-ruderman-foundation-responds-guest-column-1202130794/|title=\u2018Blind\u2019 Movie: Ruderman Foundation Responds To Director Over Alec Baldwin Casting Flap|last=Ruderman|first=Jay|date=2017-07-18|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the release of the 2016 film ''[[Me Before You (film)|Me Before You]]'', Ruderman condemned the film's widely criticized portrayal of disability, in which the protagonist{{ndash}}who is paralyzed{{ndash}}ends up committing suicide because he feels his life is not worth living. Ruderman was widely quoted as stating, \"To the millions of people with significant disabilities currently leading fulfilling, rich lives, it posits that they are better off committing suicide.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/06/05/me-before-you-ending-director-responds|title='Me Before You' director responds to controversy over film's ending|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/celebrity/celebrity-gossip/2016/6/me-before-you-movie-ending/|title=The director of Me Before You is #sorrynotsorry about its controversial ending|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref> Ruderman's second major point in this controversy was that it is problematic for an able-bodied actor to play a character with a disability, a topic he often speaks up about.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-woodburn-ruderman-disability-stats-tv-20160711-snap-story.html|title=Why are we OK with disability drag in Hollywood?|date=2016-07-11|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-03-10|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\nIn addition to commenting on movie productions, Ruderman recently has released two white papers focusing on television content and people with disabilities, as well as a white paper on first responders and suicide. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://magicvalley.com/opinion/columnists/other-view-suicide-prevention-to-priority-for-first-responders/article_fad4582a-e631-55b0-86a7-7084b1f6b673.html|title=Other View: Suicide Prevention to Priority for First Responders|last=HERALD|first=FROM THE PANAMA CITY NEWS|website=Twin Falls Times-News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> In 2019 Jay Ruderman enacted a scholarship for students with disabilities at Yale School of Drama with the goal of increasing  authentic representation for disabilities in Hollywood.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/disabled-actors-say-theyre-the-last-civil-rights-movement-in-hollywood-hardly-anyones-discussing-it/2019/01/24/cbde57a2-1817-11e9-9ebf-c5fed1b7a081_story.html</ref> Since then, Ruderman has also focused on increasing authentic representation in the entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/ruderman-foundation-responds-stronger-david-gordon-green|title=Authentic auditioning makes movies stronger, so give disabled actors a chance: advocacy group|publisher=Metro}}</ref> Despite recent improvements in authentic casting in 2020, Ruderman has emphasized that the low representation on screen had implications in shaping attitudes towards people with disabilities. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/arts/television/disabled-hollywood.html|title=For the Disabled in Hollywood, Report Finds Hints of Progress|last=Buckley|first=Cara|date=2020-02-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nRuderman works closely with actors, disability activists and celebrities in spreading awareness of disability inclusion in the entertainment industry. Some of them serve on the Ruderman Family Foundation\u2019s International Advisory Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rudermanfoundation.org/about-us/international-advisory-council/|title=International Advisory Council|website=Ruderman Family Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> Jay Ruderman also partnered with Variety Magazine for Variety\u2019s 2019 Inclusion Summit, where panelist discussed disability inclusion in entertainment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/viola-davis-julius-tennon-marlee-matlin-variety-2019-inclusion-summit-1203206549/|title=Viola Davis, Julius Tennon, Marlee Matlin to Keynote Variety\u2019s 2019 Inclusion Summit|last=Moreau|first=Jordan|last2=Moreau|first2=Jordan|date=2019-05-07|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/new-study-networks-10-billion-disabled-actors-1203354776/|title=New Study Shows Networks Leave $10 Billion on the Table by Not Casting Disabled Actors|last=Bell|first=BreAnna|last2=Bell|first2=BreAnna|date=2019-10-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> Ruderman and his wife have also been given credit for helping to bring disability inclusion to the Oscars in 2020, as Zack Gottsagen, an actor who has Down syndrome, presented an award with actor Shia LaBeouf. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishinsider.com/2020/02/how-the-rudermans-helped-bring-disability-awareness-to-the-oscars/|title=How the Rudermans helped bring disability awareness to the Oscars|last=February 10|first=Debra Nussbaum Cohen|last2=2020|date=2020-02-10|website=Jewish Insider|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2020 Sundance Film Festival, he helped to bring about more accessibility as well as inclusion of people with disabilities and diversity throughout the Festival. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sundance-film-festival-partnership-extends-accessibility-attendees-disabilities-1270602|title=Sundance Partnership Extends Accessibility for Attendees With Disabilities|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> In March of 2020, Ruderman helped bring together many in the entertainment industry to honor Peter and Bobby Farrelly with the Morton E. Ruderman Award in Inclusion for their inclusion of actors with disabilities in their movies. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/farrelly-brothers-inclusion-activism-1203524533/|title=Farrelly Brothers Saluted for Inclusion and Activism|last=Gray|first=Tim|last2=Gray|first2=Tim|date=2020-03-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn February of 2019, a group of young activists called LINK20, with the help of Ruderman, was successful in getting Major League Baseball to change its 'disabled list' to the 'injured list.' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/jewish-group-convinced-mlb-to-change-disabled-list-to-injured-list/|title=Jewish group convinced MLB to change \u2018disabled list\u2019 to \u2018injured list\u2019|last=Oster|first=Marcy|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn May of 2019, Jay Ruderman announced the Foundation\u2019s Seal of Authentic Representation. The Seal is awarded to television or feature film projects featuring actors with disabilities in substantial speaking roles, and is the premier recognition for those in the entertainment creative community who show the commitment toward full inclusiveness in popular culture.  \n\nIn November of 2015, Ruderman called out then-candidate Trump for mimicking the disability of [[The New York Times|New York Times]] writer Serge Kovaleski, who suffered from a congenital condition that affects joint movement. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nonprofitquarterly.org/ruderman-foundation-president-offers-trump-sensitivity-training/|title=Ruderman Foundation President Offers Trump Sensitivity Training|date=2015-11-30|website=Non Profit News {{!}} Nonprofit Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>  \n\nRuderman also contributes a blog on a variety of topics for ''The Times of Israel.'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/jay-ruderman/|title=Jay Ruderman's Blog|website=blogs.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> He is serving on the board of directors for the National Organization on Disability <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nod.org/about/our-board/|title=Our Board|website=National Organization on Disability|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> and on the board of governors for the University of Haifa. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/about-us/members-of-the-board-of-governors/22-hebrew/45-heb/45-prof-robert-uri-alter-usa-comparative-literature-researcher-6|title=Mrs. Shira and Mr. Jay Ruderman (Israel/USA), Philanthropists|last=User|first=Super|website=bogcms.haifa.ac.il|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n== US - Israel Relations ==\nRuderman is also active in US-Israel relations, seeking to foster a better understanding of American Jewry among Israeli opinion leaders. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/joe-lieberman-us-israel-relations-to-become-very-productive/|title=Joe Lieberman: US-Israel relations about to become \u2018very productive\u2019|last=Ahren|first=Raphael|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> \n\nHe was among several signatories of an ad expressing disappointment with the Israeli government about its decision to renege on a plan for egalitarian prayer at the Western Wall. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/major-us-jewish-philanthropists-decry-western-wall-backtrack-conversion-bill/|title=Major US Jewish philanthropists decry Western Wall backtrack, conversion bill|last=staff|first=T. O. I.|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> Ruderman also condemned the Israel\u2019s Minister of Education\u2019s comments on intermarriage of US Jews. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/education-minister-calls-intermarriage-in-us-a-second-holocaust/|title=Israel\u2019s education minister: Intermarriage among US Jews \u2018like second Holocaust\u2019|last=JTA and TOI staff|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> \n\nRuderman was quoted as saying the \"doomsday talks of an irreversible chasm between Israel and the American Jewish community were mistaken,\" in light of a recent [[Ruderman Family Foundation]] survey and in response to the notion that the bond between U.S. Jews and Israel is weakening. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/love-for-israel-survives-a-decade-of-discord/|title=Love for Israel Survives a Decade of Discord|last=Editors|first=Jewish Week|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n== COVID-19 ==\nIn response to the COVID-19 pandemic, Ruderman conveyed concerns about the effects the pandemic would have on the mental health of first responders and healthcare workers. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/12/nation/coronavirus-fight-progresses-focus-first-responders-mental-health/|title=As coronavirus fight progresses, a focus on first responders\u2019 mental health - The Boston Globe|last=Staff|first=Gal Tziperman Lotan Globe|last2=April 12|first2=Updated|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=2020|last4=Comments|first4=8:44 p m Email to a Friend Share on Facebook Share on TwitterPrint this Article View}}</ref> He also announced grants to workers at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] and the Boston Police Foundation to support their mental health. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/14/coronavirus-mental-health-medical-workers-support/|title=Coronavirus Front Lines: $100K Donation To Support Mental Health|date=2020-04-14|website=CBS Boston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 2016 Ruderman was named by ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' as one of the 50 most influential Jews of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Not-Just-News/Jerusalem-Post-50-Most-Influential-Jews-Number-46-Jay-and-Shira-Ruderman-469086|title=Jerusalem Post 50 Most Influential Jews: Number 46 - Jay and Shira Ruderman - TRENDING STORIES - Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n\n* Honorary doctorate from [[University of Haifa]], Israel (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/images/Ruderman-Heb.pdf|title=Jay, Shira Ruderman|last=|first=|date=June 2, 2015|website=University of Haifa|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Honorary doctorate from [[Brandeis University]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/2018/05/17/jay-ruderman-93-to-receive-an-honorary-degree-from-brandeis-university/|title=Jay Ruderman (\u201993) to Receive an Honorary Degree from Brandeis University - School of Law|author=|date=|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* Jacob Rader Marcus Award from the [[American Jewish Archives]] (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.org/2019/09/19/jay-and-shira-ruderman-receive-jacob-rader-marcus-award/|title=Jay and Shira Ruderman receive Jacob Rader Marcus Award|last=says|first=Suzanne Green|date=2019-09-19|website=Jewish Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* Media Access Awards [[SAG-AFTRA]] Disability Awareness Award (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/media-access-awards-honor-good-doctor-peanut-butter-falcon-nyle-dimarco-1251834|title=Media Access Awards to Honor 'The Good Doctor,' 'The Peanut Butter Falcon' and Nyle DiMarco (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n== Essays and Publications ==\n\n* Jay [https://www.jpost.com/author/jay-ruderman Ruderman's Author Page] on the [[The Jerusalem Post|Jerusalem Post]]\n* Jay [https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/author/jay-ruderman/ Ruderman's Author Page] on the [[The Times of Israel|Times of Israel]]\n* Jay [http://fathomjournal.org/author/jay-ruderman/ Ruderman's Author Page] on [[Fathom Journal]]\n*\"Ultrawealthy Donors Shouldn't Continue to Call the Shots at Jewish Charities\" on [[The Chronicle of Philanthropy|Chronicle of Philanthropy]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philanthropy.com/article/Ultrawealthy-Donors/246421/|title=Ultrawealthy Donors Shouldn\u2019t Continue to Call All the Shots at Jewish Charities (Opinion)|date=2019-06-03|website=The Chronicle of Philanthropy|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"Leveraging Israeli-Americans for the Benefit of the Wider Community\" on eJewish Philanthropy <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ejewishphilanthropy.com/leveraging-israeli-americans-for-the-benefit-of-the-wider-community/|title=Leveraging Israeli-Americans for the Benefit of the Wider Community|date=2019-12-02|website=eJewish Philanthropy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"Stop Enabling Donors Outsized Influence on Jewish Life\" on [[The Forward]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/opinion/322972/stop-enabling-donors-outsized-influence-on-jewish-life/|title=Stop Enabling Donors' Outsized Influence on Jewish Life|last=RudermanOct 22|first=Jay|last2=Ulinich|first2=2015Anya|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"People with Disabilities are the Forgotten Vulnerable\" on [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/healthcare/491616-people-with-disabilities-are-the-forgotten-vulnerable|title=People with disabilities are the forgotten vulnerable community in the age of COVID-19|last=Jordan|first=Chuck|date=2020-04-07|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRuderman is married to Israeli-American Shira Menashe Ruderman. They live in the Greater Boston area and have four children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Linde|first1=Steve|title=Jerusalem Post 50 Most Influential Jews: Number 46|url=http://www.jpost.com/Not-Just-News/Jerusalem-Post-50-Most-Influential-Jews-Number-46-Jay-and-Shira-Ruderman-469086|access-date=March 12, 2018|publisher=The Jerusalem Post|date=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruderman, Jay}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Massachusetts\u200e]]\n[[Category:Disability rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n", "text_old": "{{NPOV language|date=March 2020}}\n{{Peacock|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jay Ruderman\n| image              = Jay Ruderman April 2014.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Jay Ruderman (April 2014)\n| birth_name         = Jay Seth Ruderman\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1966|3|16}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Activist and philanthropist\n| children           = \n| parents            = Morton Edward Ruderman, Marcia Jortner Ruderman\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Shira Menashe Ruderman|2002}}\n}}\n'''Jay Seth Ruderman''' (born March 16, 1966) is an American activist and philanthropist. He is the president of the [[Ruderman Family Foundation]].\n \n==Early life and education==\nRuderman was born on March 16, 1966. He is the oldest of three siblings, the son of Marcia and Morton E. Ruderman.<ref>{{cite web | last=Negri | first=Gloria | title=Morton Ruderman, 75; devoted life to helping others | website=BostonGlobe.com | date=2011-10-31 | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/obituaries/2011/10/31/morton-ruderman-devoted-life-helping-others/rL8YpiDtdYBG1iWAWLgpwI/story.html | access-date=2018-02-22}}</ref> Ruderman attended public schools in [[Lynnfield, Massachusetts]], and received his undergraduate degree in 1988 from [[Brandeis University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandeis.edu/commencement/2018/honorees/ruderman-jay.html|title=Jay Ruderman \u201988 - Commencement - Brandeis University|author=|date=|website=www.brandeis.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> where he served as president of the student body in 1986\u201387. He earned his [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from [[Boston University School of Law]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/tag/class-of-1993/|title=Class of 1993 - School of Law|author=|date=|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> He began his career as Assistant District Attorney in Salem, MA and also worked as Deputy Director of AIPAC  before enlisting in the Israeli Defense Forces. He then went back to AIPAC as Leadership Director in Israel before taking his job at the Ruderman Family Foundation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncfp.org/people/jay-ruderman/|title=Jay Ruderman \u2013 NCFP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Commentary on popular culture==\nRuderman publicly criticized the movie ''[[Don't Worry, He Won't Get Far on Foot]]'' for casting [[Joaquin Phoenix]] in the role of a disabled man, instead of casting an actor with a disability.<ref>[https://www.indiewire.com/2018/01/joaquin-phoenix-casting-dont-worry-he-wont-get-far-on-foot-ruderman-disability-foundation-1201918359/ \"Joaquin Phoenix\u2019s \u2018Don\u2019t Worry, He Won\u2019t Get Far on Foot\u2019 Casting Slammed as Offensive by Ruderman Disability Foundation\"] ''IndieWire''. Retrieved 2018-03-22.</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Ruderman similarly condemned<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/alec-baldwin-criticized-for-portraying-blind-man-in-new-film-w491281|title=Alec Baldwin Criticized for Portraying Blind Man in Upcoming Film|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> the movie ''[[Blind (2016 film)|Blind]]'' starring [[Alec Baldwin]] and [[Demi Moore]] on grounds that Baldwin played a blind character. Ruderman's main claim is that the movie \"is just the latest example of treating disability as a costume.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/blind-alec-baldwin-controversy-1202488128/|title=Disability Organization Slams \u2018Blind\u2019 for Casting Alec Baldwin in Lead Role|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|date=July 6, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=July 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-july-disability-organization-condemns-1499273816-htmlstory.html|title=Today in Entertainment: Blue Ivy makes her rap debut on Jay-Z's new album; Angela Lansbury, Emily Watson to star in 'Little Women'|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> He likened the casting of able-bodied actors to portray characters with disabilities to blackface<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jul/06/how-alec-baldwin-casting-in-blind-is-part-of-a-catch-22-for-disabled-actors|title=How Alec Baldwin's casting in Blind is part of a catch-22 for disabled actors|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=2017-07-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and states that it's time for society to condemn the practice just like casting white actors to play black characters is no longer socially acceptable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/07/alec-baldwin-new-movie-blind-disability-rights-ableism-1201851800/|title=Alec Baldwin\u2019s New Movie \u2018Blind\u2019 Criticized By Disability Rights Group {{!}} IndieWire|last=Dry|first=Jude|website=www.indiewire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> The incident led to written exchanges between the movie's director, [[Michael Mailer]], and Ruderman, both published by the industry publication Deadline.com.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/blind-alec-baldwin-backlash-director-responds-michael-mailer-1202129011/|title=\u2018Blind\u2019 Director Addresses Backlash Over Casting Alec Baldwin And Not Disabled Actor In Lead Role|last=Mailer|first=Michael|date=2017-07-14|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-20|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/blind-movie-controversy-alec-baldwin-ruderman-foundation-responds-guest-column-1202130794/|title=\u2018Blind\u2019 Movie: Ruderman Foundation Responds To Director Over Alec Baldwin Casting Flap|last=Ruderman|first=Jay|date=2017-07-18|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the release of the 2016 film ''[[Me Before You (film)|Me Before You]]'', Ruderman condemned the film's widely criticized portrayal of disability, in which the protagonist{{ndash}}who is paralyzed{{ndash}}ends up committing suicide because he feels his life is not worth living. Ruderman was widely quoted as stating, \"To the millions of people with significant disabilities currently leading fulfilling, rich lives, it posits that they are better off committing suicide.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/06/05/me-before-you-ending-director-responds|title='Me Before You' director responds to controversy over film's ending|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/celebrity/celebrity-gossip/2016/6/me-before-you-movie-ending/|title=The director of Me Before You is #sorrynotsorry about its controversial ending|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref> Ruderman's second major point in this controversy was that it is problematic for an able-bodied actor to play a character with a disability, a topic he often speaks up about.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-woodburn-ruderman-disability-stats-tv-20160711-snap-story.html|title=Why are we OK with disability drag in Hollywood?|date=2016-07-11|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-03-10|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\nIn addition to commenting on movie productions, Ruderman recently has released two white papers focusing on television content and people with disabilities, as well as a white paper on first responders and suicide. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://magicvalley.com/opinion/columnists/other-view-suicide-prevention-to-priority-for-first-responders/article_fad4582a-e631-55b0-86a7-7084b1f6b673.html|title=Other View: Suicide Prevention to Priority for First Responders|last=HERALD|first=FROM THE PANAMA CITY NEWS|website=Twin Falls Times-News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> In 2019 Jay Ruderman enacted a scholarship for students with disabilities at Yale School of Drama with the goal of increasing  authentic representation for disabilities in Hollywood.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/disabled-actors-say-theyre-the-last-civil-rights-movement-in-hollywood-hardly-anyones-discussing-it/2019/01/24/cbde57a2-1817-11e9-9ebf-c5fed1b7a081_story.html</ref> Since then, Ruderman has also focused on increasing authentic representation in the entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/ruderman-foundation-responds-stronger-david-gordon-green|title=Authentic auditioning makes movies stronger, so give disabled actors a chance: advocacy group|publisher=Metro}}</ref> Despite recent improvements in authentic casting in 2020, Ruderman has emphasized that the low representation on screen had implications in shaping attitudes towards people with disabilities. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/arts/television/disabled-hollywood.html|title=For the Disabled in Hollywood, Report Finds Hints of Progress|last=Buckley|first=Cara|date=2020-02-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nRuderman works closely with actors, disability activists and celebrities in spreading awareness of disability inclusion in the entertainment industry. Some of them serve on the Ruderman Family Foundation\u2019s International Advisory Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rudermanfoundation.org/about-us/international-advisory-council/|title=International Advisory Council|website=Ruderman Family Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> Jay Ruderman also partnered with Variety Magazine for Variety\u2019s 2019 Inclusion Summit, where panelist discussed disability inclusion in entertainment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/viola-davis-julius-tennon-marlee-matlin-variety-2019-inclusion-summit-1203206549/|title=Viola Davis, Julius Tennon, Marlee Matlin to Keynote Variety\u2019s 2019 Inclusion Summit|last=Moreau|first=Jordan|last2=Moreau|first2=Jordan|date=2019-05-07|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/new-study-networks-10-billion-disabled-actors-1203354776/|title=New Study Shows Networks Leave $10 Billion on the Table by Not Casting Disabled Actors|last=Bell|first=BreAnna|last2=Bell|first2=BreAnna|date=2019-10-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> Ruderman and his wife have also been given credit for helping to bring disability inclusion to the Oscars in 2020, as Zack Gottsagen, an actor who has Down syndrome, presented an award with actor Shia LaBeouf. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishinsider.com/2020/02/how-the-rudermans-helped-bring-disability-awareness-to-the-oscars/|title=How the Rudermans helped bring disability awareness to the Oscars|last=February 10|first=Debra Nussbaum Cohen|last2=2020|date=2020-02-10|website=Jewish Insider|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2020 Sundance Film Festival, he helped to bring about more accessibility as well as inclusion of people with disabilities and diversity throughout the Festival. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sundance-film-festival-partnership-extends-accessibility-attendees-disabilities-1270602|title=Sundance Partnership Extends Accessibility for Attendees With Disabilities|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> In March of 2020, Ruderman helped bring together many in the entertainment industry to honor Peter and Bobby Farrelly with the Morton E. Ruderman Award in Inclusion for their inclusion of actors with disabilities in their movies. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/farrelly-brothers-inclusion-activism-1203524533/|title=Farrelly Brothers Saluted for Inclusion and Activism|last=Gray|first=Tim|last2=Gray|first2=Tim|date=2020-03-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn February of 2019, a group of young activists called LINK20, with the help of Ruderman, was successful in getting Major League Baseball to change its 'disabled list' to the 'injured list.' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/jewish-group-convinced-mlb-to-change-disabled-list-to-injured-list/|title=Jewish group convinced MLB to change \u2018disabled list\u2019 to \u2018injured list\u2019|last=Oster|first=Marcy|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn May of 2019, Jay Ruderman announced the Foundation\u2019s Seal of Authentic Representation. The Seal is awarded to television or feature film projects featuring actors with disabilities in substantial speaking roles, and is the premier recognition for those in the entertainment creative community who show the commitment toward full inclusiveness in popular culture.  \n\nIn November of 2015, Ruderman called out then-candidate Trump for mimicking the disability of [[The New York Times|New York Times]] writer Serge Kovaleski, who suffered from a congenital condition that affects joint movement. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nonprofitquarterly.org/ruderman-foundation-president-offers-trump-sensitivity-training/|title=Ruderman Foundation President Offers Trump Sensitivity Training|date=2015-11-30|website=Non Profit News {{!}} Nonprofit Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>  \n\nRuderman also contributes a blog on a variety of topics for ''The Times of Israel.'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/jay-ruderman/|title=Jay Ruderman's Blog|website=blogs.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> He is serving on the board of directors for the National Organization on Disability <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nod.org/about/our-board/|title=Our Board|website=National Organization on Disability|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> and on the board of governors for the University of Haifa. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/about-us/members-of-the-board-of-governors/22-hebrew/45-heb/45-prof-robert-uri-alter-usa-comparative-literature-researcher-6|title=Mrs. Shira and Mr. Jay Ruderman (Israel/USA), Philanthropists|last=User|first=Super|website=bogcms.haifa.ac.il|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n== US - Israel Relations ==\nRuderman is also active in US-Israel relations, seeking to foster a better understanding of American Jewry among Israeli opinion leaders. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/joe-lieberman-us-israel-relations-to-become-very-productive/|title=Joe Lieberman: US-Israel relations about to become \u2018very productive\u2019|last=Ahren|first=Raphael|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> \n\nHe was among several signatories of an ad expressing disappointment with the Israeli government about its decision to renege on a plan for egalitarian prayer at the Western Wall. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/major-us-jewish-philanthropists-decry-western-wall-backtrack-conversion-bill/|title=Major US Jewish philanthropists decry Western Wall backtrack, conversion bill|last=staff|first=T. O. I.|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> Ruderman also condemned the Israel\u2019s Minister of Education\u2019s comments on intermarriage of US Jews. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/education-minister-calls-intermarriage-in-us-a-second-holocaust/|title=Israel\u2019s education minister: Intermarriage among US Jews \u2018like second Holocaust\u2019|last=JTA and TOI staff|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> \n\nRuderman was quoted as saying the \"doomsday talks of an irreversible chasm between Israel and the American Jewish community were mistaken,\" in light of a recent [[Ruderman Family Foundation]] survey and in response to the notion that the bond between U.S. Jews and Israel is weakening. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/love-for-israel-survives-a-decade-of-discord/|title=Love for Israel Survives a Decade of Discord|last=Editors|first=Jewish Week|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n== COVID-19 ==\nIn response to the COVID-19 pandemic, Ruderman conveyed concerns about the effects the pandemic would have on the mental health of first responders and healthcare workers. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/12/nation/coronavirus-fight-progresses-focus-first-responders-mental-health/|title=As coronavirus fight progresses, a focus on first responders\u2019 mental health - The Boston Globe|last=Staff|first=Gal Tziperman Lotan Globe|last2=April 12|first2=Updated|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=2020|last4=Comments|first4=8:44 p m Email to a Friend Share on Facebook Share on TwitterPrint this Article View}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 2016 Ruderman was named by ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' as one of the 50 most influential Jews of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Not-Just-News/Jerusalem-Post-50-Most-Influential-Jews-Number-46-Jay-and-Shira-Ruderman-469086|title=Jerusalem Post 50 Most Influential Jews: Number 46 - Jay and Shira Ruderman - TRENDING STORIES - Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n\n* Honorary doctorate from [[University of Haifa]], Israel (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/images/Ruderman-Heb.pdf|title=Jay, Shira Ruderman|last=|first=|date=June 2, 2015|website=University of Haifa|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Honorary doctorate from [[Brandeis University]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/2018/05/17/jay-ruderman-93-to-receive-an-honorary-degree-from-brandeis-university/|title=Jay Ruderman (\u201993) to Receive an Honorary Degree from Brandeis University - School of Law|author=|date=|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* Jacob Rader Marcus Award from the [[American Jewish Archives]] (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.org/2019/09/19/jay-and-shira-ruderman-receive-jacob-rader-marcus-award/|title=Jay and Shira Ruderman receive Jacob Rader Marcus Award|last=says|first=Suzanne Green|date=2019-09-19|website=Jewish Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* Media Access Awards [[SAG-AFTRA]] Disability Awareness Award (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/media-access-awards-honor-good-doctor-peanut-butter-falcon-nyle-dimarco-1251834|title=Media Access Awards to Honor 'The Good Doctor,' 'The Peanut Butter Falcon' and Nyle DiMarco (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n== Essays and Publications ==\n\n* Jay [https://www.jpost.com/author/jay-ruderman Ruderman's Author Page] on the [[The Jerusalem Post|Jerusalem Post]]\n* Jay [https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/author/jay-ruderman/ Ruderman's Author Page] on the [[The Times of Israel|Times of Israel]]\n* Jay [http://fathomjournal.org/author/jay-ruderman/ Ruderman's Author Page] on [[Fathom Journal]]\n*\"Ultrawealthy Donors Shouldn't Continue to Call the Shots at Jewish Charities\" on [[The Chronicle of Philanthropy|Chronicle of Philanthropy]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philanthropy.com/article/Ultrawealthy-Donors/246421/|title=Ultrawealthy Donors Shouldn\u2019t Continue to Call All the Shots at Jewish Charities (Opinion)|date=2019-06-03|website=The Chronicle of Philanthropy|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"Leveraging Israeli-Americans for the Benefit of the Wider Community\" on eJewish Philanthropy <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ejewishphilanthropy.com/leveraging-israeli-americans-for-the-benefit-of-the-wider-community/|title=Leveraging Israeli-Americans for the Benefit of the Wider Community|date=2019-12-02|website=eJewish Philanthropy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"Stop Enabling Donors Outsized Influence on Jewish Life\" on [[The Forward]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/opinion/322972/stop-enabling-donors-outsized-influence-on-jewish-life/|title=Stop Enabling Donors' Outsized Influence on Jewish Life|last=RudermanOct 22|first=Jay|last2=Ulinich|first2=2015Anya|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"People with Disabilities are the Forgotten Vulnerable\" on [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/healthcare/491616-people-with-disabilities-are-the-forgotten-vulnerable|title=People with disabilities are the forgotten vulnerable community in the age of COVID-19|last=Jordan|first=Chuck|date=2020-04-07|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRuderman is married to Israeli-American Shira Menashe Ruderman. They live in the Greater Boston area and have four children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Linde|first1=Steve|title=Jerusalem Post 50 Most Influential Jews: Number 46|url=http://www.jpost.com/Not-Just-News/Jerusalem-Post-50-Most-Influential-Jews-Number-46-Jay-and-Shira-Ruderman-469086|access-date=March 12, 2018|publisher=The Jerusalem Post|date=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruderman, Jay}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Massachusetts\u200e]]\n[[Category:Disability rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Djjames2213", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Ruderman"}
{"title_page": "Premiership of Boris Johnson", "text_new": "{{Infobox administration\n| image = Boris Johnson on 13 August 2019.jpg\n| image_size = \n| name = Premiership of Boris Johnson\n| term_start = 24 July 2019\n| term_end = present\n| premier = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| premier_link = Prime Minister of the United Kingdom\n| cabinet = [[First Johnson ministry|1st Johnson ministry]]<br>[[Second Johnson ministry|2nd Johnson ministry]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| election = [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\n| appointer = Elizabeth II\n| seat = [[10 Downing Street]]\n| predecessor = [[Premiership of Theresa May|Theresa May]]\n| successor = \n| seal = Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom (HM Government).svg\n| seal_size = \n| seal_caption = Royal Arms of HM Government\n| official_url =\n}}\n{{Boris Johnson sidebar}}\nThe '''premiership of Boris Johnson''' began on 24 July 2019 when [[Boris Johnson|Johnson]] accepted [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]]'s invitation, at her [[Royal prerogative in the United Kingdom|prerogative]], to form a government. It followed the resignation of [[Theresa May]], who stood down as leader of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] following [[UK Parliament]]'s repeated rejection of her [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref name=\"stewart-23-July\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-elected-new-tory-leader-prime-minister|title=Boris Johnson elected new Tory leader|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThe results of the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election|leadership election]] were announced at an event in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Centre]] in [[Westminster]] on 23 July 2019. Johnson was declared leader with 92,153 votes, 66.4% of the total ballot. His competitor [[Jeremy Hunt]] received 46,656 votes. In a [[2019 United Kingdom general election|snap general election]] in December 2019, Johnson led the Conservative Party to their biggest victory since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]] (under [[Margaret Thatcher]]). Following the election, Parliament ratified Johnson's [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]], and the UK left the [[European Union]] on 31 January 2020, beginning an eleven-month transition period. \n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global pandemic]] of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]] emerged as a serious crisis within the country in early 2020, a disease particularly dangerous to the elderly and those with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-on-social-distancing-and-for-vulnerable-people/guidance-on-social-distancing-for-everyone-in-the-uk-and-protecting-older-people-and-vulnerable-adults|title=Guidance on social distancing for everyone in the UK|website=GOV.UK|date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> In late March it was announced that Johnson himself had tested positive for the disease.<ref name=COVID>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791|title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus|date=27 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=27 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Bid for Conservative leadership ==\n{{Main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n[[Theresa May]], after failing to pass her [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] through parliament three times, announced her resignation as Prime Minister of the United Kingdom on 24 May 2019 amidst calls for her to be ousted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/europe/live-news/theresa-may-resignation-announcement-0524-gbr-intl|title=Theresa May to resign as UK Prime Minister|last=Picheta|first=Rob|date=25 May 2019|work=CNN|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48379730|title=Theresa May resigns over Brexit: What happened?|date=24 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> [[Boris Johnson]] had already confirmed at a business event in Manchester days earlier that he would run for [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] leader if May were to resign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48299424|title=Boris Johnson confirms bid for Tory leadership|date=16 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nPrior to his state visit to the United Kingdom, US president [[Donald Trump]] endorsed Johnson for party leader in an interview with ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', opining that he thought he \"would do a very good job.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-48478706|title=Donald Trump says Boris Johnson would be 'excellent' Tory leader|date=1 June 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> Johnson won all five rounds of voting by MPs,<ref name=\"stewart-23-July\"/> and entered the final vote by Conservative Party members as the clear favourite to be elected PM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-on-course-to-win-tory-leadership-contest|title=Johnson on course to win Tory leadership contest|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 23 July, he emerged victorious over his rival [[Jeremy Hunt]] with 92,153 votes, 66.4% of the total ballot, while Hunt received 46,656 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49084605|title=Boris Johnson wins race to be Tory leader and PM|date=23 July 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> These results were announced an event in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Centre]] in [[Westminster]]. In his first speech as Prime Minister Johnson pledged that Britain would leave the [[European Union]] (EU) by 31 October 2019, \"no ifs or buts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/01/johnson-first-100-days-broken-promises-unlawful-prorogation|title=Johnson's first 100 days: broken promises and an unlawful prorogation|date=1 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=2 November 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Appointments ==\n{{Main|First Johnson ministry}}\nOn the day of his announcement as Prime Minister Johnson handed the role of [[Chief Whip of the Conservative Party|Chief Whip]] to \"relative unknown\" [[Sherwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Sherwood]] MP [[Mark Spencer (British politician)|Mark Spencer]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/relative-unknown-mark-spencer-becomes-chief-whip|title=Relative unknown Mark Spencer becomes chief whip|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Spencer served under the additional title [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]].\n\nAndrew Griffith, an executive at the media conglomerate [[Sky (company)|Sky]], was appointed Chief Business Adviser to Number 10. [[Munira Mirza]], who was a Deputy Mayor for Johnson throughout his mayoralty of [[London]], was appointed Director of the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/sky-executive-among-johnson-first-appointments-andrew-griffith-munira-mirza|title=Sky executive among Johnson's first appointments|last1=Syal|first1=Rajeev|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|last3=O'Carroll|first3=Lisa|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Dominic Cummings]], former chief of the [[Vote Leave]] campaign, was appointed a role as a senior advisor to Johnson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/controversial-ex-vote-leave-chief-dominic-cummings-to-join-boris-johnsons-team-in-number-10-11769523|title=Who is 'career psychopath' Dominic Cummings set to join Johnson's team?|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nJohnson's key Cabinet appointments were [[Sajid Javid]] as [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Dominic Raab]] as [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] and [[First Secretary of State]], and [[Priti Patel]] as [[Home Secretary]]. [[Michael Gove]] moved to become the [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] and was replaced as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] by pro-Brexit MP [[Theresa Villiers]]. [[Gavin Williamson]] became [[Secretary of State for Education|Education Secretary]], [[Andrea Leadsom]] became [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business Secretary]], [[Liz Truss]] became [[Secretary of State for International Trade|International Trade Secretary]] and [[Grant Shapps]] became [[Secretary of State for Transport|Transport Secretary]]. [[Stephen Barclay]], [[Matt Hancock]], [[Amber Rudd]] and [[Alun Cairns]] retained their previous cabinet roles, whilst [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]], [[Alister Jack]] and [[Nicky Morgan]] took on new roles. Entering Cabinet for the first time were [[Ben Wallace (politician)|Ben Wallace]], [[Robert Jenrick]], [[James Cleverly]], [[Rishi Sunak]] and [[Robert Buckland]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/live/2019/jul/24/boris-johnson-prepares-to-enter-downing-st-and-name-cabinet-theresa-may-prime-minister-live-news|title=Boris Johnson cabinet: Sajid Javid, Priti Patel and Dominic Raab given top jobs \u2013 as it happened|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|date=24 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 October 2019|last2=Badshah|first2=Nadeem|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Busby|first3=Mattha|last4=O'Carroll|first4=Lisa}}</ref>\n\n== First 100 days ==\n[[File:-G7Biarritz (48616722742).jpg|thumb|right|Johnson with U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] at the [[45th G7 summit|G7 summit]] in Biarritz, 25 August 2019]]\nJohnson focused on strengthening [[United Kingdom|the Union]] within his first few days in office, creating a [[Minister for the Union]] position and visiting Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.\n\n===Loss of working majority, Conservative MPs and ministerial resignations===\nOn 29 August 2019, Johnson suffered the first ministerial resignation of his premiership, when [[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|Lord Young of Cookham]] resigned as a government whip in the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/08/29/lord-young-quits-tory-whip-boris-johnsons-prorogue-stance-10650446/|title=Lord Young quits Tory whip over Boris Johnson's prorogue stance|date=29 August 2019|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2019, [[Phillip Lee (politician)|Phillip Lee]] [[Crossing the floor|crossed the floor]] and defected to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] following disagreement with Johnson's [[Brexit]] policy. This left the government with no [[working majority]] in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson loses majority after Tory MP defects during speech |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/philip-lee-tory-lib-dem-defection-boris-johnson-majority-brexit-commons-a9090356.html |accessdate=3 September 2019 |work=The Independent |date=3 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Later that day, 21 Conservative MPs including former Chancellors [[Kenneth Clarke]], [[Philip Hammond]] and [[Nicholas Soames]], the grandson of former Conservative Party Leader [[Winston Churchill]],  had [[September 2019 suspension of rebel Conservative MPs|the party whip withdrawn]] for defying party orders and supporting an opposition motion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/106279/twenty-one-tory-rebels-lose-party-whip|title=Twenty-one Tory rebels lose party whip after backing bid to block no-deal Brexit|date=4 September 2019|website=PoliticsHome.com|language=en|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> Johnson saw his working majority reduced from 1 to minus 43.\n\nOn 5 September 2019, Johnson's brother [[Jo Johnson]] resigned from the government and announced that he would step down as an MP, describing his position as \"torn between family and national interest.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49594793|title=PM's brother quits as Tory MP and minister|date=5 September 2019|access-date=5 September 2019|work=BBC News|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nOn 7 September 2019, [[Amber Rudd]] resigned as [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]] and from the Conservative Party, describing the withdrawal of the party whip from MPs on 3 September as an \"assault on decency and democracy\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/exclusive-amber-rudd-resigns-from-cabinet-and-quits-tories-06dqxcjct|title=Exclusive: Amber Rudd resigns from cabinet and quits Tories|last=Shipman|first=Tim|date=7 September 2019|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49623737|title=Amber Rudd quits cabinet and Conservative party|date=7 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Prorogation of parliament===\n{{Main|2019 British prorogation controversy}}\n\nOn 28 August 2019, Johnson advised [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] to [[Prorogation in the United Kingdom|prorogue parliament]] between 12 September 2019 and 14 October 2019, which was given ceremonial approval by the Queen at a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BBCVickiYoung/status/1166711208700981249/photo/1|title=It's donepic.twitter.com/YGdB0WX4zk|last=Young|first=Vicki|date=28 August 2019|website=@BBCVickiYoung|language=en|access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref> The prorogation spurred requests for a [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] of the advice given by Johnson as the order itself, under [[Royal prerogative in the United Kingdom|royal prerogative]] powers, cannot be challenged in court.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48936711|title=How do you suspend Parliament?|date=28 August 2019|access-date=28 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> As of 29 August, three court proceedings had been lodged, and one European legal proceeding had begun:\n\n* In the [[Court of Session]], Edinburgh, for breach of the [[Northern Ireland (Executive Formation etc) Act 2019]] and the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]], by 75 MPs led by [[Joanna Cherry]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/court-hears-challenge-boris-johnson-no-deal-brexit|title=Brexit: judge fast-tracks challenge to stop Johnson forcing no deal|last=Carrell|first=Severin|date=13 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* In the [[High Court of Justice]], Westminster, for an urgent [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] on the legality of the use of the [[Royal prerogative in the United Kingdom|royal prerogative]], by [[Gina Miller]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/28/gina-millers-lawyers-apply-to-challenge-boris-johnson-plan|title=Gina Miller's lawyers apply to challenge Boris Johnson plan|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=28 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 August 2019|last2=Carrell|first2=Severin|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* In the [[High Court in Northern Ireland|High Court, Northern Ireland]], for breach of the [[Good Friday Agreement]], by [[Raymond McCord]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/aug/29/boris-johnson-faces-third-legal-battle-over-prorogation|title=Boris Johnson faces third legal battle over prorogation|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=29 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* In the [[European Parliament]], for breach of Article 2 of the [[Treaty on European Union]], under the process outlined under [[Article 7 of the Treaty on European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-parliament-suspended-eu-rule-law-investigation-latest-a9082606.html|title=MEPs plan to trigger EU rule of law investigation into Boris Johnson's government over suspension of parliament|date=28 August 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 September 2019 the [[R (Miller) v The Prime Minister and Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland|Supreme Court of the United Kingdom found]] that Johnson's attempt to prorogue Parliament for five weeks \"had the effect of frustrating or preventing the constitutional role of Parliament in holding the Government to account\", that the matter was [[justiciable]], and therefore that the attempted prorogation was unlawful.<ref name=\"R v PM judgement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/cases/docs/uksc-2019-0192-judgment.pdf|title=JUDGMENT- R v The Prime Minister [2019] UKSC 41|date=24 September 2019|website=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Supreme Court: Suspending Parliament was unlawful, judges rule |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49810261 |accessdate=1 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=24 September 2019}}</ref> It accordingly declared that the prorogation was void ''ab initio''.<ref name=\"R v PM judgement\" /> Parliament returned the following day and the record was made to show that Parliament was not in fact prorogued but rather \"adjourned\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Parliament: MPs and peers return after court rules suspension unlawful |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49820038 |accessdate=1 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=25 September 2019}}</ref> On 2 October 2019, Johnson announced his plans to prorogue Parliament on 8 October and hold a new [[State Opening of Parliament]] on 14 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49913130|title=Parliament to be prorogued next Tuesday|date=2 October 2019|access-date=2 October 2019| work=BBC News |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Brexit plan publication ===\nOn 2 October 2019, the government delivered its Brexit proposals to the EU in a seven-page document, including plans to replace the Irish backstop. The proposals would see Northern Ireland stay in the European single market for goods, but leave the customs union, resulting in new customs checks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49909309|title=Government publishes new Brexit proposals|date=2 October 2019|access-date=2 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeremy Corbyn]], the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], said he did not think Johnson's Brexit plan would get EU support, claiming it was worse than the deal negotiated by former Prime Minister [[Theresa May]]. He also said the proposal was \"very unspecific on how the [[Good Friday Agreement]] can be upheld.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/uk/live-news/boris-johnson-brexit-offer-intl-gbr/index.html|title=Boris Johnson says his Brexit plan will not have checks at Irish border|date=2 October 2019|website=edition.cnn.com|language=en|access-date=2 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 October, government papers submitted to the [[Courts of Scotland|Scottish court]] indicated that Johnson would ask the EU for an extension to the Article 50 process if a deal was not reached by 19 October. However, later the same day Johnson reiterated his earlier statement that the UK would be leaving the EU on 31 October, regardless of whether or not a deal had been reached.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49936352|title=PM will send Brexit extension letter, court told|date=4 October 2019|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n=== Revised withdrawal agreement ===\nFollowing negotiations between the UK and EU, a revised withdrawal agreement was reached on 17 October.<ref>{{cite news|first=Holly |last=Ellyatt |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/17/uk-and-eu-agree-on-new-brexit-deal-boris-johnson-says.html |title=UK and EU agree on new Brexit deal, Boris Johnson says |publisher=NBC |work=CNBC |date=17 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> A special Saturday sitting of Parliament was held two days later to debate the new agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49984367|title=Brexit: Special sitting for MPs to decide UK's future|date=9 October 2019|website=BBC News|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/09/parliament-set-for-brexit-showdown-on-19-october|title=Parliament set for Brexit showdown on 19 October|last=Murphy|first=Simon|date=9 October 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/18/brexit-super-saturday-will-the-deal-pass |title=Brexit 'super Saturday': your guide to the big day |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> MPs passed an amendment, introduced by Sir [[Oliver Letwin]] by 322 votes to 306, withholding Parliament's approval until legislation implementing the deal was passed, and intending to force the Government to request a delay from the EU for the exit until 31 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/19/mps-put-brakes-on-boris-johnsons-brexit-deal-with-rebel-letwin-amendment|title=MPs put brakes on Boris Johnson's Brexit deal with rebel amendment|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 October 2019 |last2=Proctor|first2=Kate|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Later that evening, 10 Downing Street confirmed that Johnson would send a letter to the EU requesting an extension, but would not sign it.<ref name=\":0\" /> EU Council President [[Donald Tusk]] subsequently confirmed receipt of the letter, which Johnson had described as \"Parliament's letter, not my letter\". In addition, Johnson sent a second letter expressing the view that any further delay to Brexit would be a mistake.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50112924 |title=Brexit: PM sends letter to Brussels seeking further delay |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 October 2019 |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October, the government published the withdrawal agreement bill and proposed three days of debate for opposition MPs to scrutinise it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50132790|title=Government publishes Brexit bill|last=|first=|date=21 October 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=21 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] [[John Bercow]] refused a government request to hold a vote on the Brexit deal, citing their previous decision to withdraw it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50128740|title=MPs' vote on Brexit deal ruled out by Speaker|last=|first=|date=21 October 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=21 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe government brought the recently revised EU Withdrawal Bill to the House of Commons for debate on the evening of 22 October 2019.<ref name=\"BBC22Oct\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50146182|title=MPs reject Brexit bill timetable|work=BBC News|date=22 October 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> MPs voted on the Bill itself, which was passed by 329 votes to 299, and the timetable for debating the Bill, which was defeated by 322 votes to 308. Prior to the votes, Johnson had stated that if his timetable failed to generate the support needed to pass in parliament he would abandon attempts to get the deal approved and would seek a general election. Following the vote, however, Johnson announced that the legislation would be paused while he consulted with other EU leaders.<ref name=\"BBC22Oct\" /><ref name=\"Reuters22Oct\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu/british-parliament-backs-pm-johnsons-brexit-deal-at-important-stage-idUKKBN1X10K0|title=Brexit in chaos after parliament defeats Johnson's ratification timetable|last1=James|first1=William|last2=MacLellan|first2=Kylie|last3=Piper|first3=Elizabeth|website=[[Reuters.com]]|date=22 October 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October, Johnson took part in a one-hour and eleven minute long session of [[Prime Minister's Questions]] \u2013 the longest on record. He led tributes to parliamentarian John Bercow who stood down the following day after ten years as Speaker of the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/107659/boris-johnson-leads-tributes-tennis-ball|title=Boris Johnson leads tributes to 'tennis ball machine' John Bercow as outgoing Speaker chairs longest ever PMQs|last=Honeycombe-Foster|first=Matt|date=30 October 2019|website=PoliticsHome.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2019 general election==\n{{Main|2019 United Kingdom general election}}\n===Calls for early election===\nOn 3 September 2019, Johnson threatened to call a [[general election]] after opposition and rebel Conservative MPs successfully voted against the government to take control of the order of business with a view to preventing a no-deal exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/03/brexit-latest-news-boris-johnson-no-deal-vote-general-election/|title=Brexit vote result: Boris Johnson demands general election after rebel MPs seize control of Commons agenda|last1=Rayner|first1=Gordon|last2=Sheridan|first2=Danielle|date=3 September 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> \n \nDespite government opposition, the [[Benn Act|bill to block a no-deal exit]] passed the Commons on 4 September 2019, causing Johnson to call for a general election on 15 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49580185|title=MPs back bill aimed at blocking no-deal Brexit|date=4 September 2019|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> However, this motion was unsuccessful as it failed to command the support of two-thirds of the House as required by the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011|Fixed-term Parliaments Act]] (FTPA).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49584907|title=Johnson's call for general election rejected by MPs|date=4 September 2019|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> A second attempt at a motion for an early general election failed on 9 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/09/mps-order-johnson-to-hand-over-aides-messages-about-prorogation|title=Boris Johnson loses sixth vote in six days as election bid fails|last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=10 September 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter the programme motion for the withdrawal agreement bill failed to pass on 22 October, Johnson once again submitted a motion for an early general election under the FTPA. After the motion failed, the government put forward a short bill to hold another election \u2013 a method which needed only a simple majority and not a two thirds majority as required by the FTPA.<ref>{{cite web |title=Early Parliamentary General Election Act 2019 |url=https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-20/earlyparliamentarygeneralelection.html |website=Parliament.uk |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref> Opposition MPs submitted an amendment to change the date of the election to 9 December rather than 12 December, but the amendment failed. On 29 October, MPs approved the election for 12 December in a second vote.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK set for 12 December general election after MPs' vote |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50229318 |accessdate=1 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=29 October 2019}}</ref> The date of the election became law when [[royal assent]] was given on 31 October.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGuinness |first=Alan |title=General election: Legislation to hold early poll becomes law |url=https://news.sky.com/story/general-election-legislation-to-hold-early-poll-becomes-law-11850454 |work=Sky News |accessdate=1 November 2019 |date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaign ===\nCampaigning for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|election]] began officially on 6 November.<ref>{{cite news |title=General election 2019: Conservative Party launches campaign |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50311003 |accessdate=7 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=6 November 2019}}</ref> Johnson participated in a television debate with [[Jeremy Corbyn]] hosted by [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] on 19 November, and one hosted by the [[BBC]] on 6 December.<ref>{{cite news |title=General election 2019: Lib Dems lodge complaint over ITV leaders' debate |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50276679 |accessdate=7 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=2 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=General election 2019: Boris Johnson and Jeremy Corbyn to face off in live BBC debate |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50347661 |accessdate=11 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=8 November 2019}}</ref> He worked with Brett O'Donnell, a US [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] strategist, in preparation for the debates,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bush guru prepares Boris Johnson for election debate\n|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/in-the-blue-corner-bush-campaign-guru-prepares-boris-johnson-for-election-debate-q02zb537g|accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times|date=18 November 2019}}</ref> whilst his campaign was managed by [[Isaac Levido]], an Australian strategist.\n\nThe [[Brexit Party]] leader [[Nigel Farage]] had suggested the Brexit and Conservative parties could form an electoral pact to maximise the seats taken by Brexit-supporting MPs, but this was rejected by Johnson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.fr/us/why-johnson-will-reject-nigel-farages-leave-alliance-election-offer-2019-11/|title=Boris Johnson will reject Nigel Farage's election offer of a Brexit alliance pact|last=Colson|first=Thomas|date=2 November 2019|website=Business Insider France|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 England floods|floods]] which hit parts of England in November, Johnson was criticised for what some saw as his late response to the flooding<ref>{{cite news |first=Robyn |last=Vinter |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/nov/14/boris-johnson-flooding-flood-victims-yorkshire |title=Johnson's slow response to flooding here in Yorkshire could cost him the election |date=14 November 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-50402483/pm-boris-johnson-heckled-in-flood-hit-south-yorkshire |title=PM Boris Johnson heckled in flood-hit South Yorkshire |date=13 November 2019 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> after he said they were not a national emergency.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lucy |last=Thornton |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/flood-victim-tells-little-man-20876846 |title=Flood victim tells 'little man' Boris Johnson to 'get on his bike' after photo op |date= 14 November 2019 |work=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Conservatives banned ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' reporters from Johnson's [[campaign bus]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/mirror-barred-from-boris-johnson-campaign-battle-bus/|title=Mirror barred from Boris Johnson campaign battle bus|last=Mayhew|first=Freddy|date=21 November 2019|work=[[Press Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politics.co.uk/blogs/2019/11/22/week-in-review-tory-disinformation-campaign-intensifies|title=Week in Review: Tory disinformation campaign intensifies|last=Dunt|first=Ian|date=22 November 2019|publisher=politics.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November, Labour announced it had obtained leaked government documents; they claimed these showed that, despite claims otherwise, the Conservatives were in trade negotiations with the US over the NHS. The Conservatives said Labour were peddling \"conspiracy theories\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-nhs-trade-deal-trump-corbyn-brexit-general-election-manifesto-a9219566.html|title=Corbyn reveals secret documents that 'confirm Tory plot to sell off NHS in US trade talks with Trump|last1=Woodcock|first1=Andrew|last2=Kentish|first2=Benjamin|date=27 November 2019|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>\n\nWhilst campaigning in his constituency on 29 November, Johnson returned to Downing Street after news of a [[2019 London Bridge stabbing|stabbing]] on [[London Bridge]]. Five people were stabbed and two died from their injuries; Johnson declared the incident an act of terrorism.\n\n=== Results ===\n[[File:2019UKElectionMap.svg|thumb|A map presenting the results of the election]]\nUnder Johnson's leadership, the Conservative Party polled their largest share of votes since [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]] and won their largest number of seats since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]. Their total of 13.9 million votes was the largest number of votes won by any party since [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]. Their victory in the final contest of the election \u2013 the seat of [[St Ives (UK Parliament constituency)|St Ives]], in [[Cornwall]] \u2013 took their total number of MPs to 365, giving them a majority of 80.\n\nAfter the results of the election were announced on the night of 12 December, Johnson asked [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] permission to form a new government, and hence began organising his [[Second Johnson ministry|second ministry]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50776671|title=Election results 2019: Boris Johnson hails 'new dawn' after historic victory|work=BBC News|date=13 December 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> This remained the same as his first, aside from a new [[Secretary of State for Wales]], to replace [[Alun Cairns]], who resigned after claims that he had known about a former aide's role in the 'sabotage' of a rape trial. [[Nicky Morgan]], who had not stood in the election, and [[Zac Goldsmith]], who lost his seat, were made life peers to allow them to remain in the government.\n\n==Brexit Day to transition period ==\nOn 18 January 2020, Johnson revealed plans for the [[Brexit Day]] celebrations in Downing Street, and the commemorative coin which entered circulation on that day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/big-ben-boris-johnson-brexit-day-downing-street-celebration-a9289306.html|title=Boris Johnson announces Brexit day celebrations to distract from failure to make Big Ben bong|last=Merrick|first=Rob|work=The Independent|date=18 January 2020|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January, in its first defeat since the general election, Johnson's government lost three votes in the House of Lords over its Brexit legislation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51184051|title=Brexit: Government loses first parliamentary votes since election|publisher=BBC News|date=20 January 2020|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> However, two days later, he said the UK had \"crossed the Brexit finish line\" after parliament passed the EU bill for implementing the withdrawal agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51214761|title=Brexit: UK has 'crossed Brexit finish line', says Boris Johnson|publisher=BBC News|date=22 January 2020|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> On 23 January, the bill was given royal assent and the next day it was signed by European leaders in [[Brussels]] and by Johnson in Downing Street. The signing in Downing Street was witnessed by both British and European officials, including the Prime Minister's Europe advisor [[David Frost (British diplomat)|David Frost]]. There was a vote on the bill in the [[European Parliament]] on 29 January where it was ratified by 621 votes to 49.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51244126|title=Brexit: Boris Johnson signs withdrawal agreement in Downing Street|publisher=BBC News|date=24 January 2020|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51287430|title=Brexit: European Parliament overwhelmingly backs terms of UK's exit|publisher=BBC News|date=29 January 2020|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department for Exiting the European Union]] was closed down at 11.01pm on 31 January, a minute after the United Kingdom officially left the European Union.<ref>{{cite news|first=Nick |last=Duffy |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/brexit/brexit-secretary-steve-barclay-exits-cabinet-boris-johnson-shutters-department-1382444 |title=Brexit Secretary Steve Barclay exits cabinet as Boris Johnson shutters department |publisher=inews |date=1 February 2020 |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Brexit transition period will last until 31 December 2020, an end date that was included in [[Theresa May]]'s withdrawal agreement. Under an article of the agreement, the UK-EU Joint Committee can decide to extend the transition period by 'up to two years',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/brexit-transition-period|title=Brexit transition period|work=The Institute for Government|date=2 January 2020|access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> though Johnson plans to have signed a free-trade deal with the EU by the end of December. During this time the UK remains in the [[European Single Market|Single Market]] and [[European Union Customs Union|Customs Union]].\n\n== 2020 cabinet reshuffle ==\n{{Main|2020 British cabinet reshuffle}}\n{{See also|Second Johnson ministry}}\n\nJohnson conducted a cabinet reshuffle on 13 February 2020 when a number of senior ministers were sacked, including [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland Secretary]] [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]], [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business Secretary]] [[Andrea Leadsom]], [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[Theresa Villiers]] and [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] [[Geoffrey Cox (British politician)|Geoffrey Cox]]. Others leaving included [[Nicky Morgan]] and [[James Cleverly]]. In a surprise move, [[Sajid Javid]] resigned as [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] and was succeeded by [[Rishi Sunak]]. Javid's departure came from a refusal to comply with an order by Johnson to sack his advisory team and replace them with aides from Johnson's office.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Castle |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/13/world/europe/sajid-javid-boris-johnson.html |title=Sajid Javid, U.K. Finance Chief, Quits as Boris Johnson Shuffles Team |date=2020-02-13 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-02-13 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephen Barclay]], [[Alok Sharma]], [[Brandon Lewis]] and [[Oliver Dowden]] changed their portfolios whilst [[Anne-Marie Trevelyan]], [[Suella Braverman]], [[George Eustice]] and [[Amanda Milling]] newly joined the cabinet.\n\n== Foreign affairs ==\nOn 3 January 2020, [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike| a US airstrike in Iraq]] killed the Iranian general [[Qasem Soleimani]]. Johnson was not told about the attack by U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] prior to it happening. He was criticised for not returning from his holiday in [[Mustique]] as tensions between Iran and the west rose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/boris-johnson-trump-iran-us-war-holiday-mustique-9270371|title=Boris Johnson mocked for 'still being holiday' as tensions between Iran and the west soar|work=indy100|date=4 January 2020|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2020 review, Johnson outlined an \"overhaul\" in the UK's approach to foreign policy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51635311|title=Johnson promises 'overhaul' of post-Brexit foreign policy as he launches review|date=26 February 2020|access-date=27 February 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n=== Foreign trips ===\n{{Main|List of international prime ministerial trips made by Boris Johnson}}\n\nJohnson's first overseas trip as Prime Minister was when he travelled to [[Berlin]] to meet [[Chancellor of Germany|German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]] on 21 August 2019. He visited France to hold meetings with [[President of France|French President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]] the next day.\n\n== Domestic affairs ==\n\nJohnson welcomed a decision by political parties in [[Northern Ireland]] to restore the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] on the basis of negotiations between the British and Irish governments. Talks succeeded under [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland Secretary]] [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]] to create a [[List of members of the 6th Northern Ireland Assembly|6th Northern Ireland Assembly]], which resumed meeting on 11 January 2020. It followed a three-year hiatus with a new power sharing agreement between [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] and the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]].\n\n=== Early spending commitments ===\nOn 5 September 2019, Johnson launched a national campaign to recruit 20,000 new police officers.<ref>{{cite press release|date=5 September 2019|title=National campaign to recruit 20,000 police officers launches today|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/national-campaign-to-recruit-20000-police-officers-launches-today|publisher=GOV.UK|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe also pledged to build 40 new hospitals by 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/08/boris-johnson-40-new-hospitals-pledge-costed|title=Johnson's '40 new hospitals' pledge costed at up to \u00a324bn|last=Campbell|first=Denis|work=The Guardian|date=8 December 2019|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Transport ===\n[[File:Johnson visits Railway service in Manchester.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson delivered a speech at the [[Science and Industry Museum]] on 27 July 2019]]\nOn 27 July 2019, Johnson gave a speech at the [[Science and Industry Museum]] in [[Manchester]] where he promised to build a high-speed rail route connecting the city to [[Leeds]]. He said the project would bring \"colossal\" benefits and \"turbo-charge the economy\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-49132477|title=PM pledges new northern high-speed rail route|date=27 July 2019|access-date=28 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nJohnson came under pressure to \"pay back the trust of [[Northern England|Northern]] voters\" after his victory in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].\nThis was a factor in him giving the go-ahead to the [[High Speed 2]] (HS2) project on 11 February 2020.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51461597]</ref> The rail line, capable of speeds above 186 mph,  is scheduled to open in phases between 2028 and 2040. It has been criticised for its projected costs and impact on the environment.\n\nDowning Street said that work was underway \"by a range of government officials\" to look into the prospects of building a [[Proposed British Isles fixed sea link connections#North Channel (Kintyre) route|bridge]] from Scotland to Northern Ireland. Johnson has also promoted the idea of an airport in the [[Thames Estuary]], nicknamed \"[[Thames Estuary Airport#\"Boris Island\"|Boris Island]]\".\n\nOn 27 February, a court ruling deemed a [[Expansion of Heathrow Airport#Third runway and additional terminal|third runway]] at [[Heathrow Airport]] \"unlawful\". Johnson said he was not planning to appeal against the ruling. However, the court said that a third runway could be built in the future if it worked in line with the UK's commitments in the [[Paris Agreement]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/heathrow-expansion-boris-johnson-court-of-appeal-ruling-third-runway-a9362786.html|title=Heathrow expansion abandoned by government as Boris Johnson spokesman says it will not appeal court ruling|last1=Merrick|first1=Rob|last2=Cowburn|first2=Ashley|work=The Independent|date=27 February 2020|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 5G and Huawei ===\nOn 28 January 2020, the UK government decided to let [[Huawei]] have a limited role in building its new [[5G]] network and supplying new high-speed network equipment to wireless carriers, whilst ignoring the [[Federal government of the United States|US government]]'s warnings that it would sever intelligence sharing if they did not exclude the company. The UK government stated that they deemed Huawei as a high-risk vendor but decided against banning the company from its 5G network, and said instead that they had decided to \"use Huawei in a limited way so we can collectively manage the risk\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/28/800377277/u-k-will-allow-huawei-to-be-part-of-its-5g-network|title=U.K. Will Allow Huawei To Build Part Of Its 5G Network, Despite U.S. Pressure|publisher=NPR|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/01/in-snub-to-us-uk-will-allow-chinas-huawei-in-5g-networks/|title=In Snub to US, UK Will Allow China's Huawei in 5G Networks|last=Press|first=Associated|website=thediplomat.com|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> Several [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] members, on their part, warned against using Huawei.\n\n== Coronavirus pandemic ==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\nBy 1 March 2020, cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] had [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|reached]] every nation of the UK. Johnson unveiled the Coronavirus Action Plan and declared the outbreak a 'level 4 incident'. On 6 March he announced \u00a346 million in funding for research into a coronavirus vaccine and rapid diagnostic tests.\n\nOn 12 March Johnson said the outbreak represented the \"worst public health crisis in a generation\" after chairing an emergency [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|Cobra meeting]]. Johnson, and his team of advisers, including [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]] [[Chris Whitty]] and [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]] [[Patrick Vallance|Sir Patrick Vallance]], held daily press briefings from Downing Street to update the public on developments.\n\nThe government advised on measures such as social distancing and advised people in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions were urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and would be asked to self-isolate. Johnson announced that the UK would close the majority of its schools beginning on 20 March.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314|title=Coronavirus: UK schools, colleges and nurseries to close from Friday|work=BBC News|date=18 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> That year's summer exams were cancelled across the UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/exam-cancellations-spark-almighty-scramble-uk-admissions|title=Exam cancellations to spark \u2018almighty scramble\u2019 in UK admissions|date=2020-03-20|website=Times Higher Education (THE)|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-51643556|title=School closures: What will happen now?|work=BBC News|last=Sellgren|first=Katherine|last2=Richardson|first2=Hannah|date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, during the daily 5pm press conference, Johnson requested the closure of pubs, restaurants, gyms, entertainment venues, museums and galleries that evening, though with some regret saying \"We\u2019re taking away the ancient, inalienable right of free-born people of the United Kingdom to go to the pub\".<ref name=telegraph-20200320>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/03/20/boris-johnson-announces-extraordinary-closure-uks-pubs-restaurants/ |title=Boris Johnson announces 'extraordinary' closure of UK's pubs and restaurants in coronavirus shutdown |last=Mendick |first=Robert |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=guardian-20200411>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/11/coronavirus-exposed-myth-british-exceptionalism |title=Coronavirus has exposed the myth of British exceptionalism |last=O\u2019Toole |first=Fintan |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 April 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, in a televised broadcast, Johnson announced wide-ranging restrictions on freedom of movement in the UK, [[Coronavirus Act 2020|enforceable in law]] for a period of up to 2 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52012432|title=PM announces strict new curbs on life in UK|date=23 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=23 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> The UK had been amongst the last major European states to progressively encourage social distancing, close schools, ban public events and order a lockdown.<ref name=dw-20200401>{{cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-what-are-the-lockdown-measures-across-europe/a-52905137 |title=Coronavirus: What are the lockdown measures across Europe? |newspaper=Deutsche Welle |date=1 April 2020 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=imperial-20200330>{{cite report |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/mrc-gida/2020-03-30-COVID19-Report-13.pdf |title=Estimating the number of infections and the impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions on COVID-19 in 11 European countries |doi=10.25561/77731 |publisher=Imperial College London| work=Department of Infectious Disease Epidemiology |page=5 |date=30 March 2020 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March it was announced that Johnson had tested positive for coronavirus.<ref name=COVID></ref> On 5 April he was taken to [[St Thomas' Hospital]] in London for tests due to him displaying \"persistent symptoms\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52180223|title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson in 'good spirits' in hospital|work=BBC News|date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> He was moved to the hospital's intensive care unit the next day as his condition had worsened. [[First Secretary of State]] [[Dominic Raab]] began deputising for him \"where necessary\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52192604|title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson moved to intensive care as symptoms worsen|work=BBC News|date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> After receiving \"standard oxygen treatment\" in hospital, he was moved out of intensive care on 9 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52238276|title=PM out of intensive care but remains in hospital|date=2020-04-09|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> He left hospital on 12 April after a week of treatment, and was moved to his country residence, [[Chequers]], to recuperate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/12/boris-johnson-leaves-hospital-as-he-continues-recovery-from-coronavirus|title=Boris Johnson leaves hospital as he continues recovery from coronavirus|work=The Guardian|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=12 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n* [[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[List of Prime Ministers of the United Kingdom|British Premierships]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Premiership of Theresa May|May]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Johnson Premiership|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Boris Johnson|state=expanded}}\n[[Category:Boris Johnson]]\n[[Category:British premierships|Johnson, Boris]]\n[[Category:History of the Conservative Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:2019 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox administration\n| image = Boris Johnson on 13 August 2019.jpg\n| image_size = \n| name = Premiership of Boris Johnson\n| term_start = 24 July 2019\n| term_end = present\n| premier = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| premier_link = Prime Minister of the United Kingdom\n| cabinet = [[First Johnson ministry|1st Johnson ministry]]<br>[[Second Johnson ministry|2nd Johnson ministry]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| election = [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\n| appointer = Elizabeth II\n| seat = [[10 Downing Street]]\n| predecessor = [[Premiership of Theresa May|Theresa May]]\n| successor = \n| seal = Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom (HM Government).svg\n| seal_size = \n| seal_caption = Royal Arms of HM Government\n| official_url =\n}}\n{{Boris Johnson sidebar}}\nThe '''premiership of Boris Johnson''' began on 24 July 2019 when [[Boris Johnson|Johnson]] accepted [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]]'s invitation, at her [[Royal prerogative in the United Kingdom|prerogative]], to form a government. It followed the resignation of [[Theresa May]], who stood down as leader of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] following [[UK Parliament]]'s repeated rejection of her [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref name=\"stewart-23-July\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-elected-new-tory-leader-prime-minister|title=Boris Johnson elected new Tory leader|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThe results of the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election|leadership election]] were announced at an event in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Centre]] in [[Westminster]] on 23 July 2019. Johnson was declared leader with 92,153 votes, 66.4% of the total ballot. His competitor [[Jeremy Hunt]] received 46,656 votes. In a [[2019 United Kingdom general election|snap general election]] in December 2019, Johnson led the Conservative Party to their biggest victory since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]] (under [[Margaret Thatcher]]). Following the election, Parliament ratified Johnson's [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]], and the UK left the [[European Union]] on 31 January 2020, beginning an eleven-month transition period. \n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global pandemic]] of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]] emerged as a serious crisis within the country in early 2020, a disease particularly dangerous to the elderly and those with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-on-social-distancing-and-for-vulnerable-people/guidance-on-social-distancing-for-everyone-in-the-uk-and-protecting-older-people-and-vulnerable-adults|title=Guidance on social distancing for everyone in the UK|website=GOV.UK|date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> In late March it was announced that Johnson himself had tested positive for the disease.<ref name=COVID>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791|title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus|date=27 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=27 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Bid for Conservative leadership ==\n{{Main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n[[Theresa May]], after failing to pass her [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] through parliament three times, announced her resignation as Prime Minister of the United Kingdom on 24 May 2019 amidst calls for her to be ousted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/europe/live-news/theresa-may-resignation-announcement-0524-gbr-intl|title=Theresa May to resign as UK Prime Minister|last=Picheta|first=Rob|date=25 May 2019|work=CNN|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48379730|title=Theresa May resigns over Brexit: What happened?|date=24 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> [[Boris Johnson]] had already confirmed at a business event in Manchester days earlier that he would run for [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] leader if May were to resign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48299424|title=Boris Johnson confirms bid for Tory leadership|date=16 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nPrior to his state visit to the United Kingdom, US president [[Donald Trump]] endorsed Johnson for party leader in an interview with ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', opining that he thought he \"would do a very good job.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-48478706|title=Donald Trump says Boris Johnson would be 'excellent' Tory leader|date=1 June 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> Johnson won all five rounds of voting by MPs,<ref name=\"stewart-23-July\"/> and entered the final vote by Conservative Party members as the clear favourite to be elected PM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-on-course-to-win-tory-leadership-contest|title=Johnson on course to win Tory leadership contest|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 23 July, he emerged victorious over his rival [[Jeremy Hunt]] with 92,153 votes, 66.4% of the total ballot, while Hunt received 46,656 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49084605|title=Boris Johnson wins race to be Tory leader and PM|date=23 July 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> These results were announced an event in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Centre]] in [[Westminster]]. In his first speech as Prime Minister Johnson pledged that Britain would leave the [[European Union]] (EU) by 31 October 2019, \"no ifs or buts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/01/johnson-first-100-days-broken-promises-unlawful-prorogation|title=Johnson's first 100 days: broken promises and an unlawful prorogation|date=1 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=2 November 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Appointments ==\n{{Main|First Johnson ministry}}\nOn the day of his announcement as Prime Minister Johnson handed the role of [[Chief Whip of the Conservative Party|Chief Whip]] to \"relative unknown\" [[Sherwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Sherwood]] MP [[Mark Spencer (British politician)|Mark Spencer]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/relative-unknown-mark-spencer-becomes-chief-whip|title=Relative unknown Mark Spencer becomes chief whip|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Spencer served under the additional title [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]].\n\nAndrew Griffith, an executive at the media conglomerate [[Sky (company)|Sky]], was appointed Chief Business Adviser to Number 10. [[Munira Mirza]], who was a Deputy Mayor for Johnson throughout his mayoralty of [[London]], was appointed Director of the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/sky-executive-among-johnson-first-appointments-andrew-griffith-munira-mirza|title=Sky executive among Johnson's first appointments|last1=Syal|first1=Rajeev|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|last3=O'Carroll|first3=Lisa|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Dominic Cummings]], former chief of the [[Vote Leave]] campaign, was appointed a role as a senior advisor to Johnson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/controversial-ex-vote-leave-chief-dominic-cummings-to-join-boris-johnsons-team-in-number-10-11769523|title=Who is 'career psychopath' Dominic Cummings set to join Johnson's team?|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nJohnson's key Cabinet appointments were [[Sajid Javid]] as [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Dominic Raab]] as [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] and [[First Secretary of State]], and [[Priti Patel]] as [[Home Secretary]]. [[Michael Gove]] moved to become the [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] and was replaced as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] by pro-Brexit MP [[Theresa Villiers]]. [[Gavin Williamson]] became [[Secretary of State for Education|Education Secretary]], [[Andrea Leadsom]] became [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business Secretary]], [[Liz Truss]] became [[Secretary of State for International Trade|International Trade Secretary]] and [[Grant Shapps]] became [[Secretary of State for Transport|Transport Secretary]]. [[Stephen Barclay]], [[Matt Hancock]], [[Amber Rudd]] and [[Alun Cairns]] retained their previous cabinet roles, whilst [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]], [[Alister Jack]] and [[Nicky Morgan]] took on new roles. Entering Cabinet for the first time were [[Ben Wallace (politician)|Ben Wallace]], [[Robert Jenrick]], [[James Cleverly]], [[Rishi Sunak]] and [[Robert Buckland]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/live/2019/jul/24/boris-johnson-prepares-to-enter-downing-st-and-name-cabinet-theresa-may-prime-minister-live-news|title=Boris Johnson cabinet: Sajid Javid, Priti Patel and Dominic Raab given top jobs \u2013 as it happened|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|date=24 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 October 2019|last2=Badshah|first2=Nadeem|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Busby|first3=Mattha|last4=O'Carroll|first4=Lisa}}</ref>\n\n== First 100 days ==\n[[File:-G7Biarritz (48616722742).jpg|thumb|right|Johnson with U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] at the [[45th G7 summit|G7 summit]] in Biarritz, 25 August 2019]]\nJohnson focused on strengthening [[United Kingdom|the Union]] within his first few days in office, creating a [[Minister for the Union]] position and visiting Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.\n\n===Loss of working majority, Conservative MPs and ministerial resignations===\nOn 29 August 2019, Johnson suffered the first ministerial resignation of his premiership, when [[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|Lord Young of Cookham]] resigned as a government whip in the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/08/29/lord-young-quits-tory-whip-boris-johnsons-prorogue-stance-10650446/|title=Lord Young quits Tory whip over Boris Johnson's prorogue stance|date=29 August 2019|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2019, [[Phillip Lee (politician)|Phillip Lee]] [[Crossing the floor|crossed the floor]] and defected to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] following disagreement with Johnson's [[Brexit]] policy. This left the government with no [[working majority]] in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson loses majority after Tory MP defects during speech |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/philip-lee-tory-lib-dem-defection-boris-johnson-majority-brexit-commons-a9090356.html |accessdate=3 September 2019 |work=The Independent |date=3 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Later that day, 21 Conservative MPs including former Chancellors [[Kenneth Clarke]], [[Philip Hammond]] and [[Nicholas Soames]], the grandson of former Conservative Party Leader [[Winston Churchill]],  had [[September 2019 suspension of rebel Conservative MPs|the party whip withdrawn]] for defying party orders and supporting an opposition motion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/106279/twenty-one-tory-rebels-lose-party-whip|title=Twenty-one Tory rebels lose party whip after backing bid to block no-deal Brexit|date=4 September 2019|website=PoliticsHome.com|language=en|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> Johnson saw his working majority reduced from 1 to minus 43.\n\nOn 5 September 2019, Johnson's brother [[Jo Johnson]] resigned from the government and announced that he would step down as an MP, describing his position as \"torn between family and national interest.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49594793|title=PM's brother quits as Tory MP and minister|date=5 September 2019|access-date=5 September 2019|work=BBC News|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nOn 7 September 2019, [[Amber Rudd]] resigned as [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]] and from the Conservative Party, describing the withdrawal of the party whip from MPs on 3 September as an \"assault on decency and democracy\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/exclusive-amber-rudd-resigns-from-cabinet-and-quits-tories-06dqxcjct|title=Exclusive: Amber Rudd resigns from cabinet and quits Tories|last=Shipman|first=Tim|date=7 September 2019|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49623737|title=Amber Rudd quits cabinet and Conservative party|date=7 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Prorogation of parliament===\n{{Main|2019 British prorogation controversy}}\n\nOn 28 August 2019, Johnson advised [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] to [[Prorogation in the United Kingdom|prorogue parliament]] between 12 September 2019 and 14 October 2019, which was given ceremonial approval by the Queen at a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BBCVickiYoung/status/1166711208700981249/photo/1|title=It's donepic.twitter.com/YGdB0WX4zk|last=Young|first=Vicki|date=28 August 2019|website=@BBCVickiYoung|language=en|access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref> The prorogation spurred requests for a [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] of the advice given by Johnson as the order itself, under [[Royal prerogative in the United Kingdom|royal prerogative]] powers, cannot be challenged in court.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48936711|title=How do you suspend Parliament?|date=28 August 2019|access-date=28 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> As of 29 August, three court proceedings had been lodged, and one European legal proceeding had begun:\n\n* In the [[Court of Session]], Edinburgh, for breach of the [[Northern Ireland (Executive Formation etc) Act 2019]] and the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]], by 75 MPs led by [[Joanna Cherry]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/court-hears-challenge-boris-johnson-no-deal-brexit|title=Brexit: judge fast-tracks challenge to stop Johnson forcing no deal|last=Carrell|first=Severin|date=13 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* In the [[High Court of Justice]], Westminster, for an urgent [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] on the legality of the use of the [[Royal prerogative in the United Kingdom|royal prerogative]], by [[Gina Miller]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/28/gina-millers-lawyers-apply-to-challenge-boris-johnson-plan|title=Gina Miller's lawyers apply to challenge Boris Johnson plan|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=28 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 August 2019|last2=Carrell|first2=Severin|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* In the [[High Court in Northern Ireland|High Court, Northern Ireland]], for breach of the [[Good Friday Agreement]], by [[Raymond McCord]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/aug/29/boris-johnson-faces-third-legal-battle-over-prorogation|title=Boris Johnson faces third legal battle over prorogation|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=29 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* In the [[European Parliament]], for breach of Article 2 of the [[Treaty on European Union]], under the process outlined under [[Article 7 of the Treaty on European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-parliament-suspended-eu-rule-law-investigation-latest-a9082606.html|title=MEPs plan to trigger EU rule of law investigation into Boris Johnson's government over suspension of parliament|date=28 August 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 September 2019 the [[R (Miller) v The Prime Minister and Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland|Supreme Court of the United Kingdom found]] that Johnson's attempt to prorogue Parliament for five weeks \"had the effect of frustrating or preventing the constitutional role of Parliament in holding the Government to account\", that the matter was [[justiciable]], and therefore that the attempted prorogation was unlawful.<ref name=\"R v PM judgement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/cases/docs/uksc-2019-0192-judgment.pdf|title=JUDGMENT- R v The Prime Minister [2019] UKSC 41|date=24 September 2019|website=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Supreme Court: Suspending Parliament was unlawful, judges rule |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49810261 |accessdate=1 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=24 September 2019}}</ref> It accordingly declared that the prorogation was void ''ab initio''.<ref name=\"R v PM judgement\" /> Parliament returned the following day and the record was made to show that Parliament was not in fact prorogued but rather \"adjourned\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Parliament: MPs and peers return after court rules suspension unlawful |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49820038 |accessdate=1 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=25 September 2019}}</ref> On 2 October 2019, Johnson announced his plans to prorogue Parliament on 8 October and hold a new [[State Opening of Parliament]] on 14 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49913130|title=Parliament to be prorogued next Tuesday|date=2 October 2019|access-date=2 October 2019| work=BBC News |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Brexit plan publication ===\nOn 2 October 2019, the government delivered its Brexit proposals to the EU in a seven-page document, including plans to replace the Irish backstop. The proposals would see Northern Ireland stay in the European single market for goods, but leave the customs union, resulting in new customs checks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49909309|title=Government publishes new Brexit proposals|date=2 October 2019|access-date=2 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeremy Corbyn]], the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], said he did not think Johnson's Brexit plan would get EU support, claiming it was worse than the deal negotiated by former Prime Minister [[Theresa May]]. He also said the proposal was \"very unspecific on how the [[Good Friday Agreement]] can be upheld.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/uk/live-news/boris-johnson-brexit-offer-intl-gbr/index.html|title=Boris Johnson says his Brexit plan will not have checks at Irish border|date=2 October 2019|website=edition.cnn.com|language=en|access-date=2 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 October, government papers submitted to the [[Courts of Scotland|Scottish court]] indicated that Johnson would ask the EU for an extension to the Article 50 process if a deal was not reached by 19 October. However, later the same day Johnson reiterated his earlier statement that the UK would be leaving the EU on 31 October, regardless of whether or not a deal had been reached.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49936352|title=PM will send Brexit extension letter, court told|date=4 October 2019|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n=== Revised withdrawal agreement ===\nFollowing negotiations between the UK and EU, a revised withdrawal agreement was reached on 17 October.<ref>{{cite news|first=Holly |last=Ellyatt |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/17/uk-and-eu-agree-on-new-brexit-deal-boris-johnson-says.html |title=UK and EU agree on new Brexit deal, Boris Johnson says |publisher=NBC |work=CNBC |date=17 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> A special Saturday sitting of Parliament was held two days later to debate the new agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49984367|title=Brexit: Special sitting for MPs to decide UK's future|date=9 October 2019|website=BBC News|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/09/parliament-set-for-brexit-showdown-on-19-october|title=Parliament set for Brexit showdown on 19 October|last=Murphy|first=Simon|date=9 October 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/18/brexit-super-saturday-will-the-deal-pass |title=Brexit 'super Saturday': your guide to the big day |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> MPs passed an amendment, introduced by Sir [[Oliver Letwin]] by 322 votes to 306, withholding Parliament's approval until legislation implementing the deal was passed, and intending to force the Government to request a delay from the EU for the exit until 31 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/19/mps-put-brakes-on-boris-johnsons-brexit-deal-with-rebel-letwin-amendment|title=MPs put brakes on Boris Johnson's Brexit deal with rebel amendment|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 October 2019 |last2=Proctor|first2=Kate|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Later that evening, 10 Downing Street confirmed that Johnson would send a letter to the EU requesting an extension, but would not sign it.<ref name=\":0\" /> EU Council President [[Donald Tusk]] subsequently confirmed receipt of the letter, which Johnson had described as \"Parliament's letter, not my letter\". In addition, Johnson sent a second letter expressing the view that any further delay to Brexit would be a mistake.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50112924 |title=Brexit: PM sends letter to Brussels seeking further delay |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 October 2019 |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October, the government published the withdrawal agreement bill and proposed three days of debate for opposition MPs to scrutinise it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50132790|title=Government publishes Brexit bill|last=|first=|date=21 October 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=21 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] [[John Bercow]] refused a government request to hold a vote on the Brexit deal, citing their previous decision to withdraw it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50128740|title=MPs' vote on Brexit deal ruled out by Speaker|last=|first=|date=21 October 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=21 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe government brought the recently revised EU Withdrawal Bill to the House of Commons for debate on the evening of 22 October 2019.<ref name=\"BBC22Oct\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50146182|title=MPs reject Brexit bill timetable|work=BBC News|date=22 October 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> MPs voted on the Bill itself, which was passed by 329 votes to 299, and the timetable for debating the Bill, which was defeated by 322 votes to 308. Prior to the votes, Johnson had stated that if his timetable failed to generate the support needed to pass in parliament he would abandon attempts to get the deal approved and would seek a general election. Following the vote, however, Johnson announced that the legislation would be paused while he consulted with other EU leaders.<ref name=\"BBC22Oct\" /><ref name=\"Reuters22Oct\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu/british-parliament-backs-pm-johnsons-brexit-deal-at-important-stage-idUKKBN1X10K0|title=Brexit in chaos after parliament defeats Johnson's ratification timetable|last1=James|first1=William|last2=MacLellan|first2=Kylie|last3=Piper|first3=Elizabeth|website=[[Reuters.com]]|date=22 October 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October, Johnson took part in a one-hour and eleven minute long session of [[Prime Minister's Questions]] \u2013 the longest on record. He led tributes to parliamentarian John Bercow who stood down the following day after ten years as Speaker of the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/107659/boris-johnson-leads-tributes-tennis-ball|title=Boris Johnson leads tributes to 'tennis ball machine' John Bercow as outgoing Speaker chairs longest ever PMQs|last=Honeycombe-Foster|first=Matt|date=30 October 2019|website=PoliticsHome.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2019 general election==\n{{Main|2019 United Kingdom general election}}\n===Calls for early election===\nOn 3 September 2019, Johnson threatened to call a [[general election]] after opposition and rebel Conservative MPs successfully voted against the government to take control of the order of business with a view to preventing a no-deal exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/03/brexit-latest-news-boris-johnson-no-deal-vote-general-election/|title=Brexit vote result: Boris Johnson demands general election after rebel MPs seize control of Commons agenda|last1=Rayner|first1=Gordon|last2=Sheridan|first2=Danielle|date=3 September 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> \n \nDespite government opposition, the [[Benn Act|bill to block a no-deal exit]] passed the Commons on 4 September 2019, causing Johnson to call for a general election on 15 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49580185|title=MPs back bill aimed at blocking no-deal Brexit|date=4 September 2019|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> However, this motion was unsuccessful as it failed to command the support of two-thirds of the House as required by the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011|Fixed-term Parliaments Act]] (FTPA).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49584907|title=Johnson's call for general election rejected by MPs|date=4 September 2019|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> A second attempt at a motion for an early general election failed on 9 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/09/mps-order-johnson-to-hand-over-aides-messages-about-prorogation|title=Boris Johnson loses sixth vote in six days as election bid fails|last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=10 September 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter the programme motion for the withdrawal agreement bill failed to pass on 22 October, Johnson once again submitted a motion for an early general election under the FTPA. After the motion failed, the government put forward a short bill to hold another election \u2013 a method which needed only a simple majority and not a two thirds majority as required by the FTPA.<ref>{{cite web |title=Early Parliamentary General Election Act 2019 |url=https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-20/earlyparliamentarygeneralelection.html |website=Parliament.uk |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref> Opposition MPs submitted an amendment to change the date of the election to 9 December rather than 12 December, but the amendment failed. On 29 October, MPs approved the election for 12 December in a second vote.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK set for 12 December general election after MPs' vote |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50229318 |accessdate=1 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=29 October 2019}}</ref> The date of the election became law when [[royal assent]] was given on 31 October.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGuinness |first=Alan |title=General election: Legislation to hold early poll becomes law |url=https://news.sky.com/story/general-election-legislation-to-hold-early-poll-becomes-law-11850454 |work=Sky News |accessdate=1 November 2019 |date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaign ===\nCampaigning for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|election]] began officially on 6 November.<ref>{{cite news |title=General election 2019: Conservative Party launches campaign |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50311003 |accessdate=7 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=6 November 2019}}</ref> Johnson participated in a television debate with [[Jeremy Corbyn]] hosted by [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] on 19 November, and one hosted by the [[BBC]] on 6 December.<ref>{{cite news |title=General election 2019: Lib Dems lodge complaint over ITV leaders' debate |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50276679 |accessdate=7 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=2 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=General election 2019: Boris Johnson and Jeremy Corbyn to face off in live BBC debate |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50347661 |accessdate=11 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=8 November 2019}}</ref> He worked with Brett O'Donnell, a US [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] strategist, in preparation for the debates,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bush guru prepares Boris Johnson for election debate\n|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/in-the-blue-corner-bush-campaign-guru-prepares-boris-johnson-for-election-debate-q02zb537g|accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times|date=18 November 2019}}</ref> whilst his campaign was managed by [[Isaac Levido]], an Australian strategist.\n\nThe [[Brexit Party]] leader [[Nigel Farage]] had suggested the Brexit and Conservative parties could form an electoral pact to maximise the seats taken by Brexit-supporting MPs, but this was rejected by Johnson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.fr/us/why-johnson-will-reject-nigel-farages-leave-alliance-election-offer-2019-11/|title=Boris Johnson will reject Nigel Farage's election offer of a Brexit alliance pact|last=Colson|first=Thomas|date=2 November 2019|website=Business Insider France|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 England floods|floods]] which hit parts of England in November, Johnson was criticised for what some saw as his late response to the flooding<ref>{{cite news |first=Robyn |last=Vinter |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/nov/14/boris-johnson-flooding-flood-victims-yorkshire |title=Johnson's slow response to flooding here in Yorkshire could cost him the election |date=14 November 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-50402483/pm-boris-johnson-heckled-in-flood-hit-south-yorkshire |title=PM Boris Johnson heckled in flood-hit South Yorkshire |date=13 November 2019 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> after he said they were not a national emergency.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lucy |last=Thornton |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/flood-victim-tells-little-man-20876846 |title=Flood victim tells 'little man' Boris Johnson to 'get on his bike' after photo op |date= 14 November 2019 |work=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Conservatives banned ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' reporters from Johnson's [[campaign bus]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/mirror-barred-from-boris-johnson-campaign-battle-bus/|title=Mirror barred from Boris Johnson campaign battle bus|last=Mayhew|first=Freddy|date=21 November 2019|work=[[Press Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politics.co.uk/blogs/2019/11/22/week-in-review-tory-disinformation-campaign-intensifies|title=Week in Review: Tory disinformation campaign intensifies|last=Dunt|first=Ian|date=22 November 2019|publisher=politics.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November, Labour announced it had obtained leaked government documents; they claimed these showed that, despite claims otherwise, the Conservatives were in trade negotiations with the US over the NHS. The Conservatives said Labour were peddling \"conspiracy theories\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-nhs-trade-deal-trump-corbyn-brexit-general-election-manifesto-a9219566.html|title=Corbyn reveals secret documents that 'confirm Tory plot to sell off NHS in US trade talks with Trump|last1=Woodcock|first1=Andrew|last2=Kentish|first2=Benjamin|date=27 November 2019|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>\n\nWhilst campaigning in his constituency on 29 November, Johnson returned to Downing Street after news of a [[2019 London Bridge stabbing|stabbing]] on [[London Bridge]]. Five people were stabbed and two died from their injuries; Johnson declared the incident an act of terrorism.\n\n=== Results ===\n[[File:2019UKElectionMap.svg|thumb|A map presenting the results of the election]]\nUnder Johnson's leadership, the Conservative Party polled their largest share of votes since [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]] and won their largest number of seats since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]. Their total of 13.9 million votes was the largest number of votes won by any party since [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]. Their victory in the final contest of the election \u2013 the seat of [[St Ives (UK Parliament constituency)|St Ives]], in [[Cornwall]] \u2013 took their total number of MPs to 365, giving them a majority of 80.\n\nAfter the results of the election were announced on the night of 12 December, Johnson asked [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] permission to form a new government, and hence began organising his [[Second Johnson ministry|second ministry]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50776671|title=Election results 2019: Boris Johnson hails 'new dawn' after historic victory|work=BBC News|date=13 December 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> This remained the same as his first, aside from a new [[Secretary of State for Wales]], to replace [[Alun Cairns]], who resigned after claims that he had known about a former aide's role in the 'sabotage' of a rape trial. [[Nicky Morgan]], who had not stood in the election, and [[Zac Goldsmith]], who lost his seat, were made life peers to allow them to remain in the government.\n\n==Brexit Day to transition period ==\nOn 18 January 2020, Johnson revealed plans for the [[Brexit Day]] celebrations in Downing Street, and the commemorative coin which entered circulation on that day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/big-ben-boris-johnson-brexit-day-downing-street-celebration-a9289306.html|title=Boris Johnson announces Brexit day celebrations to distract from failure to make Big Ben bong|last=Merrick|first=Rob|work=The Independent|date=18 January 2020|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January, in its first defeat since the general election, Johnson's government lost three votes in the House of Lords over its Brexit legislation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51184051|title=Brexit: Government loses first parliamentary votes since election|publisher=BBC News|date=20 January 2020|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> However, two days later, he said the UK had \"crossed the Brexit finish line\" after parliament passed the EU bill for implementing the withdrawal agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51214761|title=Brexit: UK has 'crossed Brexit finish line', says Boris Johnson|publisher=BBC News|date=22 January 2020|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> On 23 January, the bill was given royal assent and the next day it was signed by European leaders in [[Brussels]] and by Johnson in Downing Street. The signing in Downing Street was witnessed by both British and European officials, including the Prime Minister's Europe advisor [[David Frost (British diplomat)|David Frost]]. There was a vote on the bill in the [[European Parliament]] on 29 January where it was ratified by 621 votes to 49.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51244126|title=Brexit: Boris Johnson signs withdrawal agreement in Downing Street|publisher=BBC News|date=24 January 2020|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51287430|title=Brexit: European Parliament overwhelmingly backs terms of UK's exit|publisher=BBC News|date=29 January 2020|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department for Exiting the European Union]] was closed down at 11.01pm on 31 January, a minute after the United Kingdom officially left the European Union.<ref>{{cite news|first=Nick |last=Duffy |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/brexit/brexit-secretary-steve-barclay-exits-cabinet-boris-johnson-shutters-department-1382444 |title=Brexit Secretary Steve Barclay exits cabinet as Boris Johnson shutters department |publisher=inews |date=1 February 2020 |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Brexit transition period will last until 31 December 2020, an end date that was included in [[Theresa May]]'s withdrawal agreement. Under an article of the agreement, the UK-EU Joint Committee can decide to extend the transition period by 'up to two years',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/brexit-transition-period|title=Brexit transition period|work=The Institute for Government|date=2 January 2020|access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> though Johnson plans to have signed a free-trade deal with the EU by the end of December. During this time the UK remains in the [[European Single Market|Single Market]] and [[European Union Customs Union|Customs Union]].\n\n== 2020 cabinet reshuffle ==\n{{Main|2020 British cabinet reshuffle}}\n{{See also|Second Johnson ministry}}\n\nJohnson conducted a cabinet reshuffle on 13 February 2020 when a number of senior ministers were sacked, including [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland Secretary]] [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]], [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business Secretary]] [[Andrea Leadsom]], [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[Theresa Villiers]] and [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] [[Geoffrey Cox (British politician)|Geoffrey Cox]]. Others leaving included [[Nicky Morgan]] and [[James Cleverly]]. In a surprise move, [[Sajid Javid]] resigned as [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] and was succeeded by [[Rishi Sunak]]. Javid's departure came from a refusal to comply with an order by Johnson to sack his advisory team and replace them with aides from Johnson's office.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Castle |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/13/world/europe/sajid-javid-boris-johnson.html |title=Sajid Javid, U.K. Finance Chief, Quits as Boris Johnson Shuffles Team |date=2020-02-13 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-02-13 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephen Barclay]], [[Alok Sharma]], [[Brandon Lewis]] and [[Oliver Dowden]] changed their portfolios whilst [[Anne-Marie Trevelyan]], [[Suella Braverman]], [[George Eustice]] and [[Amanda Milling]] newly joined the cabinet.\n\n== Foreign affairs ==\nOn 3 January 2020, [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike| a US airstrike in Iraq]] killed the Iranian general [[Qasem Soleimani]]. Johnson was not told about the attack by U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] prior to it happening. He was criticised for not returning from his holiday in [[Mustique]] as tensions between Iran and the west rose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/boris-johnson-trump-iran-us-war-holiday-mustique-9270371|title=Boris Johnson mocked for 'still being holiday' as tensions between Iran and the west soar|work=indy100|date=4 January 2020|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2020 review, Johnson outlined an \"overhaul\" in the UK's approach to foreign policy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51635311|title=Johnson promises 'overhaul' of post-Brexit foreign policy as he launches review|date=26 February 2020|access-date=27 February 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n=== Foreign trips ===\n{{Main|List of international prime ministerial trips made by Boris Johnson}}\n\nJohnson's first overseas trip as Prime Minister was when he travelled to [[Berlin]] to meet [[Chancellor of Germany|German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]] on 21 August 2019. He visited France to hold meetings with [[President of France|French President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]] the next day.\n\n== Domestic affairs ==\n\nJohnson welcomed a decision by political parties in [[Northern Ireland]] to restore the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] on the basis of negotiations between the British and Irish governments. Talks succeeded under [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland Secretary]] [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]] to create a [[List of members of the 6th Northern Ireland Assembly|6th Northern Ireland Assembly]], which resumed meeting on 11 January 2020. It followed a three-year hiatus with a new power sharing agreement between [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] and the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]].\n\n=== Early spending commitments ===\nOn 5 September 2019, Johnson launched a national campaign to recruit 20,000 new police officers.<ref>{{cite press release|date=5 September 2019|title=National campaign to recruit 20,000 police officers launches today|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/national-campaign-to-recruit-20000-police-officers-launches-today|publisher=GOV.UK|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe also pledged to build 40 new hospitals by 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/08/boris-johnson-40-new-hospitals-pledge-costed|title=Johnson's '40 new hospitals' pledge costed at up to \u00a324bn|last=Campbell|first=Denis|work=The Guardian|date=8 December 2019|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Transport ===\n[[File:Johnson visits Railway service in Manchester.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson delivered a speech at the [[Science and Industry Museum]] on 27 July 2019]]\nOn 27 July 2019, Johnson gave a speech at the [[Science and Industry Museum]] in [[Manchester]] where he promised to build a high-speed rail route connecting the city to [[Leeds]]. He said the project would bring \"colossal\" benefits and \"turbo-charge the economy\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-49132477|title=PM pledges new northern high-speed rail route|date=27 July 2019|access-date=28 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nJohnson came under pressure to \"pay back the trust of [[Northern England|Northern]] voters\" after his victory in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].\nThis was a factor in him giving the go-ahead to the [[High Speed 2]] (HS2) project on 11 February 2020.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51461597]</ref> The rail line, capable of speeds above 186 mph,  is scheduled to open in phases between 2028 and 2040. It has been criticised for its projected costs and impact on the environment.\n\nDowning Street said that work was underway \"by a range of government officials\" to look into the prospects of building a [[Proposed British Isles fixed sea link connections#North Channel (Kintyre) route|bridge]] from Scotland to Northern Ireland. Johnson has also promoted the idea of an airport in the [[Thames Estuary]], nicknamed \"[[Thames Estuary Airport#\"Boris Island\"|Boris Island]]\".\n\nOn 27 February, a court ruling deemed a [[Expansion of Heathrow Airport#Third runway and additional terminal|third runway]] at [[Heathrow Airport]] \"unlawful\". Johnson said he was not planning to appeal against the ruling. However, the court said that a third runway could be built in the future if it worked in line with the UK's commitments in the [[Paris Agreement]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/heathrow-expansion-boris-johnson-court-of-appeal-ruling-third-runway-a9362786.html|title=Heathrow expansion abandoned by government as Boris Johnson spokesman says it will not appeal court ruling|last1=Merrick|first1=Rob|last2=Cowburn|first2=Ashley|work=The Independent|date=27 February 2020|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n=== 5G and Huawei ===\nOn 28 January 2020, the UK government decided to let [[Huawei]] have a limited role in building its new [[5G]] network and supplying new high-speed network equipment to wireless carriers, whilst ignoring the [[Federal government of the United States|US government]]'s warnings that it would sever intelligence sharing if they did not exclude the company. The UK government stated that they deemed Huawei as a high-risk vendor but decided against banning the company from its 5G network, and said instead that they had decided to \"use Huawei in a limited way so we can collectively manage the risk\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/28/800377277/u-k-will-allow-huawei-to-be-part-of-its-5g-network|title=U.K. Will Allow Huawei To Build Part Of Its 5G Network, Despite U.S. Pressure|publisher=NPR|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/01/in-snub-to-us-uk-will-allow-chinas-huawei-in-5g-networks/|title=In Snub to US, UK Will Allow China's Huawei in 5G Networks|last=Press|first=Associated|website=thediplomat.com|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> Several [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] members, on their part, warned against using Huawei.\n\n== Coronavirus pandemic ==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\nBy 1 March 2020, cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] had [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|reached]] every nation of the UK. Johnson unveiled the Coronavirus Action Plan and declared the outbreak a 'level 4 incident'. On 6 March he announced \u00a346 million in funding for research into a coronavirus vaccine and rapid diagnostic tests.\n\nOn 12 March Johnson said the outbreak represented the \"worst public health crisis in a generation\" after chairing an emergency [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|Cobra meeting]]. Johnson, and his team of advisers, including [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]] [[Chris Whitty]] and [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]] [[Patrick Vallance|Sir Patrick Vallance]], held daily press briefings from Downing Street to update the public on developments.\n\nThe government advised on measures such as social distancing and advised people in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions were urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and would be asked to self-isolate. Johnson announced that the UK would close the majority of its schools beginning on 20 March.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314|title=Coronavirus: UK schools, colleges and nurseries to close from Friday|work=BBC News|date=18 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> That year's summer exams were cancelled across the UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/exam-cancellations-spark-almighty-scramble-uk-admissions|title=Exam cancellations to spark \u2018almighty scramble\u2019 in UK admissions|date=2020-03-20|website=Times Higher Education (THE)|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-51643556|title=School closures: What will happen now?|work=BBC News|last=Sellgren|first=Katherine|last2=Richardson|first2=Hannah|date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, during the daily 5pm press conference, Johnson requested the closure of pubs, restaurants, gyms, entertainment venues, museums and galleries that evening, though with some regret saying \"We\u2019re taking away the ancient, inalienable right of free-born people of the United Kingdom to go to the pub\".<ref name=telegraph-20200320>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/03/20/boris-johnson-announces-extraordinary-closure-uks-pubs-restaurants/ |title=Boris Johnson announces 'extraordinary' closure of UK's pubs and restaurants in coronavirus shutdown |last=Mendick |first=Robert |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=guardian-20200411>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/11/coronavirus-exposed-myth-british-exceptionalism |title=Coronavirus has exposed the myth of British exceptionalism |last=O\u2019Toole |first=Fintan |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 April 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, in a televised broadcast, Johnson announced wide-ranging restrictions on freedom of movement in the UK, [[Coronavirus Act 2020|enforceable in law]] for a period of up to 2 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52012432|title=PM announces strict new curbs on life in UK|date=23 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=23 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> The UK had been amongst the last major European states to progressively encourage social distancing, close schools, ban public events and order a lockdown.<ref name=dw-20200401>{{cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-what-are-the-lockdown-measures-across-europe/a-52905137 |title=Coronavirus: What are the lockdown measures across Europe? |newspaper=Deutsche Welle |date=1 April 2020 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=imperial-20200330>{{cite report |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/mrc-gida/2020-03-30-COVID19-Report-13.pdf |title=Estimating the number of infections and the impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions on COVID-19 in 11 European countries |doi=10.25561/77731 |publisher=Imperial College London| work=Department of Infectious Disease Epidemiology |page=5 |date=30 March 2020 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March it was announced that Johnson had tested positive for coronavirus.<ref name=COVID></ref> On 5 April he was taken to [[St Thomas' Hospital]] in London for tests due to him displaying \"persistent symptoms\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52180223|title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson in 'good spirits' in hospital|work=BBC News|date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> He was moved to the hospital's intensive care unit the next day as his condition had worsened. [[First Secretary of State]] [[Dominic Raab]] began deputising for him \"where necessary\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52192604|title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson moved to intensive care as symptoms worsen|work=BBC News|date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> After receiving \"standard oxygen treatment\" in hospital, he was moved out of intensive care on 9 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52238276|title=PM out of intensive care but remains in hospital|date=2020-04-09|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> He left hospital on 12 April after a week of treatment, and was moved to his country residence, [[Chequers]], to recuperate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/12/boris-johnson-leaves-hospital-as-he-continues-recovery-from-coronavirus|title=Boris Johnson leaves hospital as he continues recovery from coronavirus|work=The Guardian|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=12 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n* [[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[List of Prime Ministers of the United Kingdom|British Premierships]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Premiership of Theresa May|May]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Johnson Premiership|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Boris Johnson|state=expanded}}\n[[Category:Boris Johnson]]\n[[Category:British premierships|Johnson, Boris]]\n[[Category:History of the Conservative Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:2019 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Andysmith248", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premiership_of_Boris_Johnson"}
